deck_excerpt: Fallen of Kashtira V2Yu-Gi-Oh! Deck Uploaded by ZombiePuke
deck_description: A deck automatically uploaded from the Master Duel Companion App to YGOPRODeck.com. Our companion app offers a Yu-Gi-Oh! Master Duel deck tracker to assist players in tracking their deck and stats. Try it here!

A deck automatically uploaded from the Master Duel Companion App to YGOPRODeck.com. Our companion app offers a Yu-Gi-Oh! Master Duel deck tracker to assist players in tracking their deck and stats. Try it here!
Let me know how it went, success or flaws, haven't tried it but by theory, it should be good.

Naturia Control with Fusion Toolbox

This deck focuses on controlling the duel through disruption and resource management, while utilizing the "Naturia" archetype for advantage and summoning powerful Fusion Monsters.

Monsters (21):

  • Naturia Engine (13): This core group consists of various "Naturia" monsters that benefit each other. "Naturia Beast" allows searching for other "Naturia" cards, while "Naturia Camellia" recycles banished "Naturia" monsters. The deck uses a playset of "Naturia Mole Cricket" for its hand-trapping effect and swarming potential.
  • Hand Traps (6): The deck employs staples like "Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring" and "Effect Veiler" to disrupt your opponent's plays. "Ghost Ogre & Snow Rabbit" targets monsters with effects when they activate.
  • Searchers (3): "One for One" and "Lonefire Blossom" help search for specific monsters, while "Spore" can be used to bring out "Naturia Beast."
  • Other (2): "Rose Lover" offers revival for Plant monsters, and "Snowdrop the Rikka Fairy" provides some searching utility.

Spells (17):

  • Draw Power (2): "Pot of Prosperity" fuels your hand advantage, while "Foolish Burial" sets up graveyard effects for monsters like "Naturia Exterio."
  • Disruption (4): "Called by the Grave" removes threats from your opponent's graveyard, while "Super Polymerization" allows for powerful Fusion Summons using monsters on both sides of the field. "Solemn Judgment" negates powerful effects.
  • Naturia Support (3): "Naturia Blessing" offers protection and search for "Naturia" monsters.
  • Utility (8): "Waking the Dragon" revives a Level 5 or higher monster, "Naturia Sacred Tree" provides additional resources, and "One for One" helps search for specific monsters.

Traps (2): None in this build, focusing on proactive strategies.

Extra Deck (15):

  • Naturia Fusions (3): "Naturia Exterio" is a powerful boss monster, while "Naturia Barkion" and "Naturia Beast" offer additional control and swarming options.
  • Generic Fusions (7): "Starving Venom Fusion Dragon" steals ATK, "Predaplant Dragostapelia" negates effects, and "Mudragon of the Swamp" provides removal. The deck also includes "Psychic End Punisher" for piercing damage, two copies of "Trishula" for negation and removal, and "Draco Berserker of the Tenyi" for a strong beatstick.
  • Other (5): "Black Rose Dragon" offers board clearing, "Teardrop the Rikka Queen" searches for Plant monsters, "Aromaseraphy Jasmine" negates effects, and "S:P Little Knight" provides a Link Summoning option.

Overall Strategy:

This deck aims to disrupt your opponent's plays with hand traps and "Called by the Grave" while building advantage through the "Naturia" engine and card draw. You can then use "Super Polymerization" to create powerful Fusion Monsters like "Naturia Exterio" to take control of the duel. The versatile toolbox Extra Deck offers options for various situations.
One sheep, two sheep, many more sheep.

> TCG legal format:
All cards are tournament legal.

deck_excerpt: Those who call the Sanctuary in the Sky home do not like visitors. Show those trespassers the divine wrath of angels.
deck_description:
So, this is a deck for a format called Domain! Rules of deckbuilding are simple, for those unaware.

1. 60 card main, 15 card extra deck, singleton, no banlist.
2. I can use any spells and traps I desire, however I can only use cards that fit my "Deckmaster's Domain", in this case my Deckmaster is the Harest Angel Of Doom (Hence it being in my sideboard). Domain consists of all cards of the Deckmaster's attribute, type, any archetypes listed in their name, as well as any attributes, types, archetypes, and exact statlines listed in the Deckmaster's text, with the exclusion of reminder text (aside from archetypal, like summoned skull being an archfiend).

In this case, I can use any dark monster, and any fairy monster. So, I decided to go with Sanctuary In The Sky, a mix of Counter Fairies, Parshath, and The Agents! I want opinions on this. Also, the Barian's Chaos Draw is really supposed to be a Seventh Tachyon, but it wasn't on here when I moved the deck in.

Goal is simple. Control the board, and beat face while they have nothing. More difficult as this is singleton and against 3 other people, but that's what I like about this deck- the challenge. Plus, it makes Iron Thunder hilarious due to the way collumns work in Domain, hehe.

deck_name: Winged Dragon of Ra- Ogdoadic- Horus 100% (never bricks)
deck_excerpt: Winged Dragon of Ra- Ogdoadic- Horus 100% (never bricks)
deck_description:
Winged Dragon of Ra 100% (never bricks)

My favorite card of all time, the one that got me into yugioh, was the Winged Dragon of Ra. It got me to try master duel, and start my whole journey. 

My second favorite archetype was Ogdoadic, because I raise and care for reptiles, and the just looked like the would go perfectly with Ra. I was able to make a deck with Bishbaalkin, the one from DarkArmedDuelists channel, that essentially let me add Slifer and Ra, and use them pretty consistantly without having to normal summon. But once Bishbaalkin was banned that deck was no longer usable on masterduel. I was no longer able to use both in a useable way. In comes Horus (which Horus himself looks like Ra). It lets us increase our starters and get maximum consistancy.

HOW THE DECK WORKS

Deck Breakdown:

12 starters:
Ogdoadic: 3x Nunu, 3x Nauya
Horus: 3x Imsety, 3x King's Sacophagus

9 Conditional starters/extenders:
Ogdoadic: 3x Ogdoadic daybreak, 1x Ogdoadic Serpent Strike, 1x Ogdoadic Water Lily, 1x Zohah
Reptile: 1x Black Mamba, 1x Night Sword Serpent, 1x I.A.S. Invasive Alien Species

9 Bricks (extenders when sent to graveyard, often with Horus engine):
2x Guardian Slime, The Ogdoadic Light & Dark, Both Ogdoadic Overlords, Blessing, Protection and Guidance of Horus

10 Ra Summons/Seachers:
2x Winged Dragon of Ra, 2x Sphere Mode, 3x Ancient Chant, 3x The True Sun God

Exta deck:
Necassary: Fera Imps is needed for the Nunu 1 card combo
Conditional:
-Galaxy-eyes cards optional, 2 card destroyed on the field, change of heart that can be used as material for rank up, protection for light monsters, or an omni-negate.
-Number 97 engine and Nummeron Dragon optional, just for OTK if you dont get Ra, a spell negate, or defense piercing dmg
-Alien Shocktrooper and Cosmic Slicer, optional, especially if you go first, and can get lots of tokens on the field, it  basically negates all on field opponent monsters and changes them to defense position, if you add alien kid to the deck and swap it out with one of the non Ogdoadic Reptile cards.
-Lizadose Optional, banish reptile from gy draw one
-Echidina Optional, makes an opponents monster 0 atk, good for OTK

Goal of the Deck:
To get Ra on the field going 2nd with a 6 card hand basically every single hand in a digitially shuffled or a well in person shuffled deck. I have tested 20 hands and was always able to either get Ra on the field, or  3/20 instances go into Nummeron Dragon or Galaxy-Eyes Dragon. The following figures are based upon the Yugioh Probability Calculator.

Basically we have 12 starters that can each individually get 3 bodies on the field for Ra, as a 1 card combo(nunu is the only one that would require using a normal summon to get 3 monsters on the field, the other 9 require no normal summons), and combined with the 9 situational starters (situation being 1 normal summonable reptile monster), we are going to have about 92.93% chance to open with 2 of any of these 21 cards. 
But if we just want to concider the 12 starters, we have a 90.18% chance to draw at least 1 of them.

With 10 Ra cards, we have a 84.53% chance to draw at least 1 Ra card. (Im not counting Guardian Slime which is classified as a brick/conditional extender, but if we include it, it rises to 90.18%)

With 9 Brick/Conditional Extender Cards, we have a 80.82% chance to draw at least 1, 40.98% chance to draw at least 2, and an 11.47% chance to draw at least 3, and an 1.63% to drawing at least 4. 

Basically you are competing against a very small likelyhood you would draw 3 or 4 bricks, and there is an exremely high likelyhood you will draw at least 1 one card combo starter, and a Ra/Searcher. (If you add 3 Ashes and 3 Maxx C, for 46 cards, it lowers the chance to pull 1 one card starter combo by 5%, so it goes from 90% to 85%)

The combo starts with lady past and light on the field (you can summon, one for one, hikari or fortune visions -> lady calling them).
Activate past's effect to increase her level, using light. Activate light's effect to summon lady water, synchro summon 999 times charge warrior and catastor with desynchro for bootleg pot of greed. You should end up with zoroa, a 2/3 monsters apo if you manage to hold calling and a bunch of useless shit. Half of the deck (dangers/magicians soul) is used to draw stuff, to get free bodies and to recycle the useless crap in hand.

deck_description: This is a time lord synchron mikanko deck that is meant for staple cards. It's a good combo deck that uses something fun and is different from other strategies.

This is my attempt at a competitive ancient gear deck, while not meta, i would consider it rogue in local / regional environments, and there are further improvements to be made.

This deck focus's on using board breakers to invalidate a built up board, as well as gaining as much advantage through its own engine as possible.

Tech choices:

Way Where There's a Will : This card is amazing for this deck. You want access to engine and access to board breaking, which this card gives you easy access to going second, and considering how actively we destroy spell/traps, we stop the opponent recieving the same advantage. This card can be used to fish for whatever you are missing, Whether thats board breakers or engine, while also being able to mitigate its cost by putting back brick / duplicate cards e.g. Ancient Gear Box 

Urgent Schedule : This card is essentially its own form of board breaker with the addition of two tech cards:

  • Magical Hound : This acts as not only a +1 in card advantage in heavy spell/trap matchups, but also provides an out for cards like skilldrain, that this deck can usually not play through in the slighest, e.g. schedule into hound and a 5 or higher, link into ballista and dont use eff, hound to return skill drain, link 2 into a second ballista for its effects.
  • Infinitrack Tunneller : this card acts as a better target for dark golem in most situations, as well as allowing you to recycle your monsters after a successful ancient gear fusion (you essentially mill 4 ancient gear monsters)

Some tips for this deck i will mention:

When choosing what fusion spell/trap to use, know it depends:

  1. if your opponent is playing a heavy removal deck but focus's on spell/traps, fusion is the safe option, as chaos giant will most likely survive until the battle phase
  2. how many monsters are on the board? if it is full, its best to use chaos giant to deal as much possible peirce damage as possible, if there are few, ancient gear duel can give you a 4400 beatstick that will swing 3 times with peircing, most likely winning you the game if theres an empty board.
  3. Duel will protect your golems from monster based interuption, and will be more useful in certain duels
  4. Is your opponent Tempai? if you can keep chaos giant alive until battle phase, then they wont have access to their activated monster effects, buying you precious time 

I have played with a actual golem to use commander, but i feel like it then becomes glued to my hand and it causes lots of bricks. You could experiment with 1 of each golem, but prepare to loose to one runick spell if your unlucky.

Note: With support in the form of dragon and Statue, this deck gets some more options for going second, mainly being able to replace frame and being able to summon wyvern later into an uninterupted combo, more akin to the geartown catapult 2 card combo which generates significant advantage.

When playing with dark golem, judge your need of the fusion spell with the cards in your hand / grave, if you havent used catapult in summoning it (tanker usually or a popped geartown), you can add geartown catapult, discard catapult, and give your access to an additional monster, if tanker hasnt been used, this may fetch your searchers for the fusion spells later, while allowing you to more efficiently delay your opponent with chaos giant / bagooska pass, or chaos giant + dugaress for double attack.

Work in progress. Basically this is what happens when I try to figure out how to make Ashened work.

V1: Pure Ashened

By God it doesn't work. Don't let those YouTube videos with all their bombastic titles fool you. Cross my heart, this deck when run pure is just Dark Hole Dragon with extra steps. You'll wonder why the field is empty, then you'll realize you did all that yourself in the first place... on turn 1. Just don't.

V2: Ashened Gaia

Fusion Armament from Duelist Nexus gave the deck a nice tech: Gaia Prominence, The Fierce Force. For some reason both it and its named material Gaia Blaze, Force of The Sun are both Pyro monsters. That's a monster negate in 4 summons, insulating you from a certain space rock. However, it trades with your main Ashened line, resulting in a weaker Veidos due to being summoned with less materials.

V3: Ashened Despia

When you think of Fusion-centric decks, Branded is the first thing that comes to mind, so I drafted this up. Obviously we can't fit the entire arsenal in here, but with what few cards that fit in, it does wonders for the deck. God bless Albaz.

It gives you extra body rapidly, plays around your locks (you can even apply two locks -Fusion and Pyro- and still play through if you know what you're doing), but most importantly: it gave the deck an objective to build towards.

Basic gameplan here is to make sure you always have an access to a Fusion Summon. Where do the materials come from is a secondary concern-- Branded doesn't care. Haven't playtested this one as of the initial post, will update when I have more data.

deck_excerpt: Hand discard engine with warrior toolbox
deck_description:
The core is the usual warrior engine, considered x2 don Zaloog but felt too fragile. Kycoo for chaos. Asura priest and spear dragons for Goats and combos with robbin goblin to get huge discards in one turn or when opponent sets/has goats. Triple bladeknight for damage and BLS. Warrior returning alive is an underrated pick that can substitute the second Zaloog. Back to square one is a strong removal that bounces on top of deck, goes together in combo with DROP OFF, which is the focus of the deck together with time seal. Other traps are pretty standard. 

Side dust and sakuretsu for warriors, sasuke for spy, archer for burn. Others are optional, feel free to suggest better cards.

Thought the Solfa cards were cute and decided to try and build a deck involving them! Ty for any feedback! :)
deck_description:
Thought the Solfa cards were cute and decided to try and build a deck involving them! Ty for any feedback! :)

Melodious and Solfachord are two very similar archetypes, both of them incorporate fairy types pendulum monsters and a strong love for music! It's basically a match made in heaven. To give more consistency to the deck, I added a Herald + Hierarchia core, which perfectly supports this deck as it allows for an easy Cutia from the deck!

Solfachord's boss monster, GranSolfachord Coolia, is a very cool piece for an endboard, as it acts as an omninegate! She also provides fantastic extra zones for Pendulum summons. With Solfachord's main strength being its ability to fill the extra deck with face-up Pendulum monsters, it is a way to gain additional bodies fairly easily, therefore providing the deck a solid endboard!

This deck's most important combo is the one described in this video from ggGio on youtube, the classic Melodious routing. https://youtu.be/RIr6P_NUIrY?si=ie5FK5JldlOBAtRd

s/o to Anoter for helping me build this prototype, ty bro <3

deck_excerpt: The new Masterduel SKY STRIKER MOBILIZE - ENGAGE animation is CLEEAAAANNNNN!
deck_description:
The new SKY STRIKER MOBILIZE - ENGAGE animation is CLEEAAAANNNNN! It definitely adds extra satisfaction resolving the card seeing all the bright and shiny lights in addition to our +1 "Pot of Greed" card.

The idea behind Blind Second Sky Strikers is to wipe out most if not all of your opponent's resources that they slap down on the board going first, and then close out the match with Sky Striker's grind game. Everyone in the Fusion/Link Event is slapping down their entire extra deck and main deck and hand into the board going first and you'll just wipe all that away with your ~20ish boardbreakers!

If you want quick easy games to grind for the Fusion/Link Event, Blind Second Sky Striker is perfect for that!

If you have any questions about this deck, feel free to ask me in the comments below!

GLHF Duelists!

deck_excerpt: gaslight, gatekeep, girl boss during your opponent's Draw Step
deck_description:
*PRETEND FOSSIL DIG IS SEVENTH TACHYON*

Recently, a new Spell card called "Seventh Tachyon" was revealed which proves to be a powerful card for many Xyz decks. One of those decks just so happens to be Generaider, one of my favorite decks!

Since Loptr is a Level 4 Fairy monster, you can reveal Number 102 Star Seraph Sentry to search not only Loptr, but also Condemned Witch, another card that can get you into Loptr AND a "Forbidden" Quick-Play, either Droplet or Chalice.

This one card gives the deck more consistency, which it's needed for a while. Don't get me wrong, Vala fixes bricked hands, which is amazing. But on it's own, it doesn't do much.

deck_description:
Joshua Schmidt 520 Player Spring Challenger Cup..

2nd Place.

The idea of this deck is to avoid all the turn skip combos and play during your opponents turn. The R-Ace is comparable to Maxx-C, but it can trigger any of your tear cards, or cycle a transaction/trivikarma. Since you play so much trap cards, you can't set them all if they play into your maxx c, you can mill yourself with the tearcards also it's less likely that your op would negate a R-Ace on a blind pick.

deck_name: Dancing Big Koala looking for the sun!
deck_description:
On the island perched upon the ancient back of the Great Turtle{Island Turtle (4042268)}, relentless rain had poured for days. Amidst the downpour, Big Koala {Big Koala (42129512)}, the arboreal dancer, grew increasingly discontent. With each sway of his limbs and shake of his branches, he beseeched the heavens for reprieve, his movements a whimsical plea for the sun's return.

 

Meanwhile, deep within the heart of an inscrutable mountain, Kageningen {Kageningen (80600490)} braced for a transformation wrought with danger. Jagged spikes would soon erupt from its rocky facade, signaling a threat to any who dared approach. As the metamorphosis neared completion, Ryu-Kishin{Ryu-Kishin (15303296)} emerged, a monstrous form poised to wreak havoc upon the land.

 

Beneath the storm-laden skies, a mournful howl shattered the silence, echoing through the valleys and reaching the heavens above. Silver Fang {Silver Fang (90357090)}, the vigilant guardian, raised his voice in a desperate cry, imploring the gods to end the deluge. As if in response, lightning crackled and thunder roared, illuminating the approaching terror of Ryu-Kishin.

On the island which is the back of the Turtle {4042268}; the rain has been no stop for days now. Big Koala {42129512} is not happy with the rain looking to the sky wondering the waters has not stopped enjoying his tree dance waving it around hoping for the sky’s notice. In an unknown mountain somewhere closed, mid-center on the Turtle, Kageningen {80600490} Which is about to transform into something painful and with spikes from it. Something to run from as soon as someone lays on it! Ryu-Kishin {15303296} after the transformation is this monster gotten to a whiff of the moist air, took off jumping for the mountain and jumping from tree to tree, and hears a howls from the grounds a wolf, Silver Fang {90357090}, Whom cries to the sky’s to stop and the lighting strikes right by wolf; Ryu-Kishin lep rights as the sounds thunders hits. Silver Fangs see the monster, and just then wake up from the nightmare smelling something good in the air.

deck_name: The Island Chronicles: Tales of Triumph, Turmoil, and Temptation
deck_description:
Silver Fang {90357090} stirred from his restless slumber, still haunted by the horrifying encounter with Ryu-Kishin {15303296} within Fang's nightmare, drawn by the irresistible aroma of cooking meat. With determination born of hunger, he began to crawl towards the source of the savory scent, his senses sharpened by the promise of a hearty meal.

 

Meanwhile, Under the radiant sun, Big Koala {42129512} revealed itself in the warmth of the cloudless sky. Yet, despite the idyllic day, a strange sadness gripped him, weighing heavy on his usually cheerful demeanor. As he ambled through the sun-dappled foliage, the cause of his melancholy remained a mystery, lurking just beyond his grasp.

 

In another corner of the Island Turtle {4042268}, two warriors sat by their campfire, basking in the afterglow of their recent victory over a mighty Garnecia Elefantis. Their masks removed, they bore the marks of battle: M-warrior 1's {56342351} face marred by chemical burns, a testament to his relentless pursuit of strength; and M-warrior 2's {92731455} skin adorned with leaf-shaped scars, souvenirs of his lazy dalliance beneath the unforgiving sun.

 

As they bantered about their conquest, M-warrior 1 boasted of their triumph over the beast. "Garnecia Elefantis {49888191(?)} was the easiest kill," he declared with a hint of swagger.

 

M-warrior 2 chuckled at his companion's bravado, teasing, "If that's your idea of an easy kill, I shudder to think what you'd consider tough."

 

A hearty laugh escaped M-warrior 1's lips. "Well, then, my friend," he jested, "the toughest kill on this island would be us!"

 

Their mirth was interrupted by the sudden appearance of Silver Fang, who darted towards the fire, seizing a piece of meat from under their noses. Startled, the warriors exchanged bewildered glances, momentarily taken aback by the audacity of the wolf.

 

The start with the Koala happy with the sunny sky, but for some weird reason felt saddened and we soon found out why! As the silver wolf woke from his nightmare smelling good cooked meat; he started to crawl that way! Two warriors after setting up camp, started taking cooks there, most recently killed Garnecia Elefantis, an elephant, so big each step shakes the ground which was easy for the warrior to find the monster! As Silver Wolf crawled slowly to the smell; M-warrior 1 took his mask off to find his face with chemical burns, looking for new strengths. He had said "Arg was the easiest kill." M-warrior 2 tooken his mask off just to find leaves shaped burns from the sun; when he was lazy sitting under the tree staring at the sun, and falling asleep from not wanting to do the day's work. M-warrior2 said in remark of the M-warrior 1 "If you called that an easy killed; I am afraid to see what you called a tough kill" M-warrior 1 just laughs “Hey dummy that would be us. We would be the toughest killed on the islands”

M-warrior 2 also laughs at the idea of something that would kill them. The smell of the beast got Silver fang to run tores the fire and grab a piece of the meat under the two warriors' noses!

deck_excerpt: Fight alongside the Lightsworn by wielding the incredible powers of Runick!
deck_description:
Before the arrival of modern graveyard powerhouses that like Tearlaments and Ishizu, Lightsworn was the OG "mill" predecessor of this style of dueling. It is the first fully dedicated milling archetype debuting in "Light of Destruction" all the way back in 2008. Almost exactly 16 years later with the release of Legacy of Destruction, Lightsworn returns with some much needed power-ups! 
 
Lorewise, Lightsworn are a group who seek to save those who ask for help, crossing time and space in order to help them. Consuming vast quantities of magical energy, these heroes appear, vanquish villains and disappear once the job is done. Now you can join them yourself in their crusade to smite evil by wielding the incredible powers of Runick! With Lightsworn's mills and Runick's control, you should be able to drown your opponent with card advantage while you foil their every move with your quick-play spells! 

Inspired by World Champion Joshua Schmidt's recent Runick Lightsworn Locals victory and video, I've created a guide to Lightsworn Runick based on my own experience playing the deck. And believe me, if you like control and milling as a gameplay mechanic, you'll find this deck extremely fun to pilot! Draw 9 times, mill nearly your entire deck and obliterate evil with Runick Lightsworn!
 
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 
ARCHETYPES AND DECKBUILDING
 
As the name implies, Lightsworn Runick is mainly composed of the two archetypes. 

The LIGHTSWORN portion is fairly large, composed of 19 cards. Just based on how the milling mechanic works, you want to hit your luck-based mills as much as possible. So the more mill worthy cards, the more plusses you get! Once the ball gets rolling, Lightsworn nets you incredible amounts of resources and mills, especially since many of their older cards don't have a "once per turn" clause. Generally, Lightsworn monsters provide you with tuners for synchro plays, level 4 bodies for rank 4 plays, so in addition to your Runick interruption in-hand, you get a board full Lightsworn defending you! 
 
RUNICK offers an alternative win condition of this deck by banishing your opponent's deck. Runick also increases the deck's consistency and grindgame since it allows for a draw 1-3 per turn. With some luck in combination with Lightsworn, Runick can draw 7-9 cards in one turn due to the recycling of Runick Fountain with Runick Geri and Daigusto Emeral. Runick spells also break opponent's boards fairly well when played correctly in tandem Lightsworn - 2 level 4 bodies can make Bagooska or S:P Little Knight with her banish. Runick offers solid defensive options, with Hugin protecting against destruction effects, Munin protecting from targeting effects and Geri dissuading the opponent from attacking. 
 
Contrary to other decks, Runick Lightsworn has only 2 STAPLES cards due to the nature of the strategy - almost the whole deck is engine due to the necessity of proper mills. I chose Mudora and Keldo, GY shufflers as well as level 4 bodies for XYZ/synchro plays. 
 
40 cards are mandatory since it is a mill deck that needs as much consistency as possible. 
 
COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN
 
The strategy of Lightsworn Runick is to control/banish your opponent's resources until they surrender or deck-out. Compared to other Runick variants like Bystial or Generaiders, Lightsworn is less "control" oriented and trades it for more resources. Lightsworn milling cards into the GY grant the pilot an incredible amount of card advantage and field presence, since the combination of Runick + Lightsworn typically draws 5+ cards and mills 15+ cards to the GY. In addition to that, Lightsworns have very easy access to rank 4 threats like Bagooska and level 8/10 synchros bosses like Dis Pater and Chengying. 
 
After you've drawn, milled and combo'd, Lightsworn Runick usually has a 4-6 cards hand, a packed GY full of Runick spells, and a full field composed of S:P Little Knight, 
 
There are few "combos" for Lightsworn Runick due to the random nature of the mills this deck offers - with each random mill, you get different resources for different plays. I'd advise you to practice with test hands what to do in particular gamestates to play this deck optimally since it isn't linear. 
 
Anyways, here is the single bread and butter combo line for Lightsworn:
 
Weiss, Lightsworn Archfiend + Level 4 Lightsworn = Mill 9 cards to pack your GY + potential draw 0-3
  1. Activate Weiss' effect to place the level 4 Lightsworn on top of the deck and summon itself and to mill 2 cards. 
  2. The level 4 Lightsworn summons itself with it's own effect. 
  3. Synchro summon Minerva, the Athenian Lightsworn using Weiss + Level 4 Lightsworn.
  4. Activate Minerva's synchro summon effect to send to the GY Weiss and Felis, Lightsworn Archer. 
  5. CL1 activate Weiss to summon the level 4 Lightsworn from your GY, CL2 activate Felis' effect to summon herself from the GY. 
  6. XYZ summon Minerva, the Exalted Lightsworn using Felis + Level 4 Lightsworn. 
  7. Activate Minerva the Exalted's effect to mill 3 cards from deck and draw cards equal to the number of lightsworn cards milled. 
  8. Activate Minerva, the Athenian's effect to banish 4 Lightsworns from the GY to mill 4 cards. 
The deck's endboard is generally varies due to the mills that this deck can get. You can potentially resolve Runick Fountain's draw effect repeatedly due to the recycling effects of Runick Geri and Daigusto Emeral for a whopping draw 9-12! The pilot can also end on a mix of Bagooska's field-wide "skill drain," S:P Little Knight's banish, Chenying's banish, and Dis Pater's negate/destroy. The GY may have the Ishizu shufflers in it, while your hand and backrow are full of Runick quick-play interruption. Also if you've sided in Skill Drain and Powersink Stone, that may be set in the backrow as well!
 
With the immense resource advantage in hand and GY both Lightsworn and Runick offers, your opponent should wither away while you snowball to victory!
 
GENERAL TIPS
  • Similarly to Sky Striker, this is a toolbox control resource deck. It has a high skill ceiling since it factors in a player's decision making, resource management and match-up knowledge. Practice makes perfect with the deck!
  • Bagooska can be used as a pseudo-boardbreaker. If your opponent somehow allows you to have 2 level 4 monsters on board at the same time, you can shut down all their face up non-link monsters by XYZ summoning Bagooska! Bagooska doesn't affect you too much, since you can freely use your Runick spells still and most of your Lightsworn effects activate in the hand or GY rather the field. You can "turn off" Bagooska by linking it away into S:P Little Knight. 
  • Another card that can be placed in this deck instead of the Ishizu shufflers is "The Black Goat Laughs." It can be used if milled to help break boards or prevent your opponent from using a certain card. It can also be used as discard fodder by Runick Hugin.
  • Due to Runick Geri and Daigusto Emeral, Runick Fountain can be recycled over and over again - potentially meaning that you can draw up to 9 cards! Geri Recycles Fountain from the GY, while Geri + another level 4 can make Daigusto Emeral to recycle Geris from the GY. Keep looping this recycling so you can keep drawing with Runick Fountain! 
  • Dis Pater can only be made with Lightsworn Dragonling in this deck, since it is the only non-tuner Dragon. The best way to make Dis Pater is using Dragonling + Tri-Edge Master. 
  • The best cards to side out are x1 Smiting Storm, x1 Dispelling, x2 Ishizu shufflers, x1 Charge of the Light Brigade, x1 Solar Recharge, x1 Wulf, and x1 Felis. 
     
    Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 
CONCLUDING REMARKS
 
Fight alongside the heroes of justice and light with Lightsworn Runick! Vanquish evildoers with the combined forces of interdimensional heroes and your arsenal of quick-play Runick weapons! 
 
Lightsworns has been a longtime oldschool favourite of mine. I'm so glad they have a chance to shine in the competitive spotlight!
 
Shoutout as usual to the GOAT Joshua Schmidt for cooking, piloting and teaching Lightsworn Runick. Drawing three with Runick Fountain has never been more reliable and easy when Lightsworns mill so much to the GY!
 
GLHF Duelists!

deck_excerpt: Lair of Darkness tag teams with Fang of Critias fusions and Zeus (because why not)
deck_description:
PLEASE READ: (And comment, it helps)

Updates: removed malicous engine for better consistancy, and replaced it with superpoly engine. larger range of useful traps and higher qualitly side deck. removed No75 as you're just going to want to go into Darius anyway.  Currently experimenting with red blossoms, will keep this version more updated.

Basically a Lair of Darkness tribute spam with Ladys of lamet, searching either Crush Card or Mirror Force for Critias fusions, also optional Mask Change II for gy and hand control if you are struggling with floating effects and hand traps.

pretty much anything is swapable for whatever you want to add, like handtraps in side if you need and other possible engines (these are just my personal favourites on the list).

Pot of Prosperity is not required but helps a tone when searching for literally anything you need, run as many as possible if you have the funds but is not required for the base engines to function, just seriously helps with unbricking etc.

Extra Deck is Beat cop for lair protection, and decode for board protec building from beatcop.

Zeus Package with D/D/D Darius,

Dark Law and critias fusions with generic super poly targets aswell (will be further thought out soon)

 Optional engines

Bystial,

Super poly,

Malicious + armageddon knight + foolish,

Zeus package,

(technically Critias but that's kinda the point of this),

...

should be legal, hopefully...

but will update if not

Read Less
Utilizing the Horus engine, P.U.N.K. engine, and Zombies to beat down opponent or provide enough time to eventually cycle Blue Dragon Flute Summoner and Selene to draw the remaining pices of Exodia

deck_name: Ecstatic Reverie: A Celestial Ode to the Night Skies
deck_description:
I wanted this story to be just about big koala but i am not good at writting 

Big koala looking into the night sky after eating his tree! Just smiling at how peaceful life is,  looking into the night sky seeing all the lights from the stars and the 3 different moons he sees, but don't truly understand where, how and why they are there. So happy to see the different lights and there in the distance shooting stars so many different of them, creating a wave of different colors. One flows of purple, another blue, yellow, green, magnificent scarlets. Big koala looking in awe and amazement over the show in the night skies! 

 

GPT edit:

Ecstatic Reverie: A Celestial Ode to the Night Skies

 

In the ethereal embrace of the nocturnal expanse, behold Big Koala, his countenance aglow with a serene radiance, gazing skyward with rapture unparalleled, having partaken of the nourishing fruits of his arboreal abode. His visage, a testament to the tranquility that permeates existence, bespeaks volumes of the sublime harmony he finds in the cosmic tapestry unfurled before him.

With an effervescent grin adorning his features, Big Koala beholds the firmament, a celestial canvas adorned with the resplendent luminance of myriad stars and the trifecta of lunar orbs, whose origins, mechanisms, and celestial choreography elude the grasp of mortal comprehension. Yet, in their enigmatic dance across the heavens, he finds solace and wonder, a testament to the boundless majesty of the cosmos.

Amidst the cosmic ballet, a veritable symphony of shooting stars cascades across the heavens, each ephemeral luminary painting the heavens with a kaleidoscope of chromatic splendor. Behold, as a veritable torrent of hues unfolds, cascading in waves of iridescence: regal purples, cerulean blues, golden yellows, verdant greens, and crimson scarlets, each a testament to the infinite palette of the cosmos.

In the thrall of this celestial spectacle, Big Koala stands enraptured, his spirit uplifted by the spectacle unfolding before his eyes. With awe unbridled and amazement unbound, he beholds the cosmic pageantry, a witness to the timeless dance of the stars. Thus does he stand, a humble observer amidst the grandeur of the night skies, his soul alight with wonder and reverence for the ineffable beauty that surrounds him.

deck_name: Tales from the Wild: Echoes of Fury
deck_description:
Tales from the Wild: Echoes of Fury

The heavy-lidded gaze of Big Koala, weary from witnessing the vibrant explosions of color in the nightly sky, and slightly squinting from the glare of the scorching sun. With a sigh, the large koala rises and shifts to the next barren tree, resigned to its task of munching on the bark, for lack of anything else to occupy its time.

Silver Fang, rousing from slumber beside the river after his evening meal, decides to plunge into the water in search of fish. Instead, he encounters Souleater {31242786}, a wise fish imbued with telepathic knowledge acquired over ages. Through thought alone, Souleater reassures Silver Fang, conveying that the ordeal is nearly at its end. Enraged, Silver Fang attempts to strike Souleater, but the elusive fish swiftly darts away, leaving Silver Fang unable to pursue. Fuming with frustration, Silver Fang eventually succumbs to exhaustion and drifts off to sleep.

Perched on a tree branch, M-warrior 2 awakens under the scorching sun, his gaze drifting to the remnants of the Garnecia Elefantis feast. Amidst the ashes of the extinguished fire, he spots a skeletal reminder of a Mammoth Graveyard {40374923}, etched into his memory. Descending from the branch, he resolves to seek out the companionship of M-warrior 1, noting that at least the camp area remains untouched despite M-warrior 1's anger.

M-warrior 1, still seething with anger after a sleepless night spent relentlessly attacking trees, lashes out at any creature that dares to approach, questioning who the true monster really is. Amidst the chaos, he spots a Petit Moth {58192742}, one of the ingredients for the Paralyzing Potion {50152549} gifted by the Dancing Elf {59983499} in hopes of enhancing his power. However, instead of empowerment, it merely renders him unconscious, leaving him vulnerable to the elf's razor-winged dance of cuts. Frustrated by the memory of their mocking laughter, he swings wildly at the air, compelling the new elves to retreat without inflicting harm this time. A Petit Angel {38142739}, trailing the elves, meets its end as M-warrior 1 hurls a lance, silencing it in the growing light of dawn, which seems to echo his fury. As the sun rises, its angry glow attracts the attention of a Whiptail Crow {91996584}, drawn towards the tumultuous sounds caused by M-warrior 1.

orignal:

The eyes of Big Koala, heavy from watching the stars explode with color in the nights; Slightly open from looking at the hot sun. The big koala sighs as he had gotten up and moved to the next uneating tree, and started eating the tree. 

 

Silver Fang, sleeping by the river waking up from his dinner from the night before; decide to to  jumps in the water and look for a fish, but instead meets with Souleater {31242786}; A fish wised from age that gains telepathic knowledge from all his knowledge. With his thought he told the Silver Fang not to worry; it was almost over. Angrily Fangs try to attack Souleater. Souleater just swam aways so fast that the silver fang could not follow. On the tree branch M-warrior 2 waking up from the hot sun decides to see if any of the meats are left from the Garnecia Elefantis. Looking at the ashes left from the fire and seeing a boney composed remembrance of a Mammoth Graveyard {40374923} from the branch. Leaps downs decided to look for company M-warrior 1. At least he didn’t didn’t destroy the camp area as he thought. 

 

M-warrior 1 Still angry after staying up all night lancing and beating the tree’s. Attack any monster who gets closed; wondering who really is the monster. All the Petit Moth {58192742} which one of the ingredients of Paralyzing Potion {50152549} that the Dancing Elf {59983499} had given him so he could gain more power, but sadly it just knock him out and the elf to dancing around with her razor wings to cut him all over. Wrath of Nature - TAG FORCE 1 GAME
Echoes of the Forest: Tales of the Unseen
deck_description:
Echoes of the Forest: Tales of the Unseen

 

After voraciously consuming three trees, including their trunks and branches {sadly, aspens made from willow bark}, the Big koala found himself perplexed by the curious gazes of the surrounding birds. Realizing he had inadvertently devoured their homes, he picked up the last branch and began to dance, attempting to shoo them away with an apologetic gesture.

 

Upon leaping from the cliffs into the forest depths, the demon Ryu-Kishin spotted a whiptail crow soaring overhead, its presence accompanied by a cacophony of violent cries emanating from the depths of the foliage. Driven by curiosity, the demon trailed the creature, drawn inexorably towards the source of the ominous sounds.

 

Startled awake by the tumultuous cries echoing from the nearby streams, Silver Fang's anger still simmered from the encounter with the mystical souleater and its ominous warning. Determined and resolute, he set off towards the source of the morning's violent lamentations, driven by a mix of curiosity and the need to confront whatever darkness lurked ahead.



M-Warrior 2, vigilant at the campsite, startles at the distant cries, recognizing them as his missing companion's. Relief washes over him, tinged with concern. Realizing it's his friend, he chuckles to himself, swiftly heading towards the sounds, eager to reunite and tease his comrade about his distress.

The Big koala, just devoured three trees, the whole trunks and branches {sadly aspins is made from willow bark}; wondering why all the birds around him looking at him, after eating all their homes, he pick-up the last branch and started to dance to shoo them aways! 

 

The demon Ryu-Kishin, after jumping off the cliffs onto the forest below; sees a whiptail Crow in the air, and hears a violent cry coming from somewhere hidden in the trees! Unknowing the demon followed the beast which was headed towards the sounds.

 

Silver Fang woke from the violent crying coming from an area by somewhere close to the streams! Still angry about the mystical souleater, and souleater warning; decided to head towards the morning violent cries! 

 

M-warrior 2 looking after looking at the campsite hears the angry cries, and to his wonder knowing it was his missing companion! Those cries are from him as he thinks out loud and aims towards the sounds!

deck_excerpt: This is not a good deck.
deck_description: This is funny, but please do not play this.

This isn't a deck I intend for you to just copy-paste into Master Duel, Duel Links, or just buy the cards. I'm here to give you tips and ideas to create your own Dinosaur deck. Moreover, this deck is actually based on Dinosaurs. You can insert your generic negate cards if you want, but I'm remaining a purist for this guide. 

Main Deck: The Transcendosaurus archetype can not only be made into its own deck, but its requirement of one spell and two mai deck monsters ( Xeno Meteorus and any Normal Dino) lets it drop into any deck you want. The archetype thrives in destroying cards, and uses them to get off combos. The availability of cards means that you can get out a lot of different extra deck monsters a lot easier than you used to, while still having space for staple main deck monsters like Ultimate Conductor Tyranno. Due to the focus on level 6 monsters, it's important to spread out your arsenal, and have a lot of methods to get them out, whether it be destroying monsters like usual Dino combos, or getting them out with cards like Jurassic Power or The Monarchs Stormforth. There's a lot of possible combo starters and paths you can go down, the biggest starters being Animadorned Archosaur, Miscellaneousaurus, and Ground Xeno. Using monsters like Horned Saurus can also help extend and branch your combos. 

The Transcendsaurus cards all share the effect to summon themselves when they're destroyed. Keep that in mind, since card that use destruction as cost can be used on them. You can also use this for interesting plays. Trap cards like Oops! can be used to quickly destroy your cards which can get you in and out of different situations. For example: if your opponent is threatening your board with Ghoti of the Deep Beyond (which would banish everything on the field), you can use High Rate Draw to destroy your monsters so they go to the grave rather than being banished. Not onlly that, but Transcendosaurus cards will bring themselves back, and make Glaciasaurus' effect live. You can also use a destruction trap to attack with a monster, destroy it, bring it back, and attack again. 


Extra Deck:

Thanks to the generic Dinosaur's flexibility and access to cards like Scrap Raptor, you have a lot of cards at your disposal; just keep in mind that Xeno cards lock you into Dinos, Dragons, Sea Serpents, and Wyrms. Experiment with cards you like and figure out an Extra Deck that suits you.  


Other options:

One thing this deck suffers from is something YuGiOh players call a Garnet, referring to a card you want to have in your deck to call upon, but is pretty hard to work with if its in your hand. Because of this, it's nice to have ways to make these cards useful. One thing Normal monsters are good for is paying cost, since they want to be in the graveyard anyways. Cards like the True Kings or Dragon Ruler cards do well with this since there is decent variety of attributes for Normal Dinosaurs. Other simpler cards like Evoltile Megachirella who simply discard work just as well. 

Beta Evolution Pill - Ultranscendance will let you cheat dinosaurs from your deck and extra deck. While it doesn't let you ignore the conditions of main deck monsters like UCT or Overtex Qoatlus, it can cheat out extra deck Dinosaurs. These monsters you cheat out could be good, but keep in mind that they are not summoned properly. This means "If this card is Fusion/Synchro/XYZ/Link summoned" effects won't activate, and if they are sent to your grave you can't summon them back. 

From here, feel free to put in whatever cards you feel, whether they be combo starters, bodies, or hand traps.

deck_excerpt: Numeron The King of budget decks
deck_description:
Based off of Dark Armed Duelist's Numeron Deck Profile in January. I decided to change my Slifer Numeron deck into two different decks. I went away from Numeron with Slifer and made it into a Slifer Knights deck, and took the Numeron portion and made it a Pure Numeron deck. 

You will probably very rarely go into the side deck, but I put in some different options for board breakers depending on the situation or how many monsters your opponent summons. I also opted for an Instant Fusion + Millennium-Eyes Restrict combo, Called By the Grave, and some Solemn Judgements to cover a multitude of effects and activations that could hurt your game plan. Also there is some heavier backrow hate if it is needed.

deck_excerpt: S:P Little Knight joins the demon dogs of destruction as they tear their way through Masterduel ladder, destroying everything in their path!
deck_description:
S:P Little Knight joins the demon dogs of destruction as they tear their way through Masterduel ladder, destroying everything in their path!

Having S:P Little Knight as a link summon target for Unchained Soul of Rage not only means you get to link away an opponent's monster - with S:P you can 2 banishes! S:P also protects your board against a myriad of threats, especially Evenly Matched. On top of that, Unchained is basically full power in Masterduel, only held back by the ever present and annoying Maxx "C."

If you want a detailed guide and step-by-step combo list, check out my article from earlier this year.

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

GLHF Duelists!

Gravekeeper's ft. Helpoemer

Set Helpoemer face down then swap it over with Creature Swap, before running over it with one of your own guys to make sure it's destroyed by battle. (That or just crash it into something bigger!). From then onwards (whilst it's protected in the GY with Necrovalley), your opponent will be forced to discard a card after every battle phase for the rest of the duel, all whilst you gain value with Stele and co, whilst denying them their GY effects, to grind out tto a victory.

Eldlich with a side of Tenpai
deck_excerpt: When your eldlich has had enough
deck_description:
The deck functions as a primarily Eldlich deck confusing people at tournaments before you side out all 15 eldlich cards with the 15 tenpai. Opponents are caught off guard and generally don't have a play around it. 

 

And yes you can be basic af and use Labyrinth instead of Eldlich.
I think this would be a fun concept to think about but honestly haven't tried it yet so let us seeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeee

Skeleton for a Harpie deck, with minimal non-engine. The deck mainly aims to swarm then control with Cyber Slash and the traps. There's a chance Feather Storm is a bit too powerful for the power level I'm aiming for, but it can be switched if that's the case.

The alternatives include a few archetypal cards for fun, some typal / attributal link monsters, Phalanx Pike can pump a monster to hilarious heights, Summon Storm is probably not needed but could increase the swarming in the grind, Cowrie & Nest can provide negation dodging, hand shaping and help trigger some trigger effects on summon by switching out monsters, but it probably is too low impact, Three of a Kind is funny.
A dangerous path the cryptids lead to Dark World!

deck_excerpt: Gaia the Dragon Champion and BLS

deck_description:
Invoked Shaddoll deck by zephyr wargames.

I reccommend swapping S:P Little Knight for Knightmare Unicorn if it's too expensive. You can also swap out "Artemis, the Magistus Moon Maiden" and "I:P Masquerena" for "Salamangreat Almiraj" and "Secure Gardna", if you need a way to get a fire monster in the graveyard for an Invoked Purgatrio play.

Alternative Builds

Super Polymerization - replace 2 "Effect Veiler", 2 "Triple Tactics Talents", "Artemis, the Magistus Moon Maiden", and "I:P Masquerena" for 3 "Super Polymerization", "Nibiru the Primal Being", "Mudragon of the Swamp", and 'Garura, Wings of Resonant Life".

Dogmatika - replace 2 "Effect Veiler", 2 "Triple Tactics Talents", "Artemis, the Magistus Moon Maiden", and "I:P Masquerena" for 3 "Nadir Servant", "Dogmatika Maximus", "Elder Entity N'tss", and "Titaniklad the Ash Dragon". You can also remove 1 "Shaddoll Squamata", then add "Dogmatika Fleudelis, the Knighted" and "Dogmatika Ecclesia, the Virtuous".

deck_excerpt: Apollousa Bow Goddess + Ravenous Tarantula + Evigishki Neremanas + Secret Village of the Spellcasters
deck_description:
Gishki-Lock Deck 

Check my YouTube channel MattasticFilmsReal for deck profile and combo.

This is a Gishki lock deck which forces the opponent out of monster and spell effects. To play, loop the draw power of Gishki Zielgigas, using Evigishki Neremanas, as well as utilizing other draw cards. This way reducing your LP and thinning through your deck, adding more resources to your hand and field. 

The goal is to bring Apollousa onto the field while having around 1000 LP left, then bring back 2 or 3 Neremanas, a Gishki Zielgigas (XYZ this and a Neremanas for Ravenous Tarantula) and if you open well an Evigishki Soul Ogre. At the end of these plays, activate a Secret Village of the Spellcasters. 

You end the turn with an Apollousa with over 10k ATK points (essentially unlimited monster negates), a Ravenous Tarantula in DEF position. Ideally 2 Neremanas and a Gishki Soul Ogre, for two monster neg (+ it is a Quick Effect). You also have a Secret Village of the Spellcasters on the field whose effect holds as you have a Neremanas on board. Thus your opponent is SPELL AND MONSTER EFFECT LOCKED.

In End Phase, you can use Focused Aquamirror for Aqua Mirror set to field for next turn plays, One Day of Peace means that you will not take damage during your Opponent's turn. Into the Void will also dump your hand to grave. 

This is a first turn deck, but use side cards for going second. OTK is still quite solid.

Thanks for reading.

deck_description: Normal Swarm/Beat with Fiends, effect focused side.

This deck uses a Kuriboh engine to provide fodder for Destiny HERO - Plasma. Summon Kuriboh with The Flute of Summoning Kuriboh or Stygian Security, then tribute Kuriboh with Multiply to generate a bunch of tokens. Plasma tributes monsters to special summon himself, so you can use the tokens without worry!
This deck was original builded by Dark Armed Duelist

My take on a Floo build. After getting cooked by a stun player running Decisive Battle of Golgonda, I was thinking to myself, "What deck could benefit from something like this?"

The first deck I thought of were the funny Normal Summoning birds. With combat protection just in case Empen falls through, which may not be often, and getting to search Albaz for a budget Super Poly, I think it's an interesting little tech.

Also, Gold Sarc is literally just RotA for the deck when opening another bird and it's such a nice feeling having an Ash proof way to search Robina.

Play this in the Edison Format. At the time of uploading, YGOPRO's deck builder did not allow Chain Material in an Edison Format deck.

Fusion summon Destiny End Dragoon or Elemental HERO Absolute Zero as soon as possible to put tremendous pressure on your opponent! Search for your key combo pieces with Elemental HERO Stratos and Elemental HERO Prisma. Chain Material is great for summoning Destiny End Dragoon because he can revive himself during your Standby Phase. You can also use Book of Moon or Interdimensional Matter Transporter to avoid Chain Material's destruction effect.

Side Deck Tech

Super Polymerization is super effective against earth and water decks, but it can also be used to fusion summon Destiny End Dragoon during your opponent's turn with Chain Material.

This is a fun Reasoning deck, but it is fairly prone to bricking.

Assuming you know how the Solfachord cards work, the main spice here is using Diviner of the Herald as a starter. Send Trias Hierarchia with the effect then use Trias's effect to tribute Diviner and special summon Cutia from deck, then use the Cutia and Hierarchia on field to start linking off. Protecting Spirit Loagaeth is another neat tech card that synergizes pretty well with the deck and can put in a lot of work in some situations, but typically you'll be using it as a second material to go into Beyond the Pendulum.

For your turn one end board, if you open good you should be able to end on GranSolfachord Coolia (the Link-3), a set Solfachord Musica (search it with SolSolfachord Gracia), and at least an odd-scale Solfachord monster in your pendulum zone to fuel Coolia's omni-negate. Ideally you have DoSolfachord Coolia as the odd-scale that you special summon with the Link-3's negate, which gives you an additional pop. On later turns, establish Gracia and Angelia with an odd and even scale to stun your opponent during your battle phase.

The idea is to augment the Mayakashi core with an Eldlich engine, since it mainly plays out of the main deck so you can play around the Extra Deck xeno-lock on some of the Mayakashi cards. If you can manage to do the full Mayakashi combo and dump your synchro monsters into the graveyard, you can get additional summons of them using the Eldlixir cards. Alternatively, if you open mostly Eldlich cards, you can use the Eldlixirs to special summon Hajun to get everything started.

The Zombie World package is also in here, although you could consider cutting them to add in more of your main engine for more consistency, since you do run the risk of opening the wrong mix of cards at times. Like any Eldlich deck, this deck has a pretty good grind game, but this version requires a lot of balancing between the two main engines.

focus on yusei deck in anime final arc that his deck seem like can fiting for add signer dragon from his friend even he (should) not actually had time to modify his deck. so i design this deck to can switch exta deck for using signer dragon but also can play his own synchron warrior card too.

Like Snake-Eyes, one of the main appeals of this archetype is that it uses a small core engine, so you can cram a bunch of hand traps and board breakers in to fill out the gaps.

Lava Golem and Small World go together. You can bridge it to Dreaming Nemleria using Ash Blossom, or turn an Ash Blossom into any of the Level 10 beasts. Fenrir and Unicorn are mostly to bait out handtraps. Eater of Millions is at 1 because I only have the one copy. It can let you use Dreaming Nemleria's effect very early, but be careful because you might want the ED fuel for cards like Repeter or Dream Tower.

The Extra Deck could be almost anything, the only main one you would want is Linkuriboh, or another Link-1 that you can use to get Dreaming Nemleria back on top of the Extra Deck after using its effect. Theoretically you can make Baronne de Fleur using one of the Kashtira monsters plus Ash Blossom, and then Psychic End Punisher is an option using one of Dream Defenders and Effect Veiler. From there just pick a Rank 10 toolbox, although Gustav Max and Liebe are good options for closing out games.

This is adapted from the deck I built for the Dark vs. Light event. The deck revolves around establishing D-Tactics and Break the Destiny, but because they aren't searchable, I use a critical mass of Destiny HERO names in order to fuel Destiny Draw. Verte Anaconda puts in a lot of work for the deck, so I don't know if I would recommend trying it out outside of Master Duel.

For your main combo, assuming you see Break the Destiny, then fusing into Dominance actually provides a lot of value, particularly if you can do so using Fusion Destiny. Because Break the Destiny destroys your monster for cost, you can trigger Dominance's graveyard effect to special summon 3 different Destiny Heroes. Typically you'll want Dreadmaster among them for the battle protection, and then usually I would go for Denier and Disk Commander to dig deeper into my deck. Denier in particular gets a lot chances to shine in this deck since you'll get the chance to do more than just re-stack Malicious into your deck.

Other than that, D-Tactics pairs really well with Dystopia and DPE, and is searchable with Break the Destiny's graveyard effect. Unforunately, Destiny End Dragoon isn't very playable in this deck, since it isn't actually a Destiny HERO monster, so it conflicts with Cross Crusader's and Faris's xeno-lock.

deck_excerpt: Want to win Yugioh with a unga bunga beatdown deck just like back then? Just "ask your friends for a copy of Trident" Dragion!
deck_description:
Have you tried "asking your friends" for a copy of Trident Dragion? (good joke btw Komoney)! Or did you randomly have the guy in your bulk from 2009? Well you're in luck, since Tenpai Dragons have made this card extremely powerful and competitively viable!

For the "year of fire's" finale and acknowledgement of the "year of the Dragion" for the Chinese New Year, Konami has really outdid themselves this time. Through a field full of monsters, hand full of handtraps, gamestate with plentiful interruption, Tenpai Dragons can still obliterate all your opponent's lifepoints EASYYYY!

One turn kill your opponent with the force of a million suns with the combined absurdly high attack power of Dragion - 36400 total lifepoint damage! Not only are these dragons unaffected by activated effects during Main Phase 1 through their archetypal field spell, these cards are so consistent with 16 one card starters that you can jam about 25 staples into the deck! You can inundate your opponent with a flurry of handtraps and boardbreakers then proceed to their final reckoning as you enter battle phase.

JOIN THE TENPAI GANG AND OBLITERATE YOUR OPPONENT WITH THE FORCE OF A THOUSAND NUCLEAR BOMBS!

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 
ARCHETYPES AND DECKBUILDING 
 
Not mixed with any other archetypes, Tenpai Dragon is usually played "pure." This deck has so many staples in it while being consistent that duelists sometimes say the Tenpai player is using a OTK engine in a handtrap deck!
 
The TENPAI cards are a potent, compact and consistent OTK strategy composed primarily of 1-card starters. Almost every Tenpai card has as much potential and gas as "Branded Fusion" and "Snake-Eyes Ash!" This deck core uses 3 Sangen Summoning (searcher field spell), 3 Sangen Kaimen (emergency teleport), 3 Tenpai Chundra (summons from deck), 3 Tenpai Paidra (spell/trap searcher) and 2 Fadra (quick efffect synchro summon - the only non-starter). Terraforming, Set Rotation and Pot of Prosperity count as additional 1 card starters, effectively granting this deck 17 1-card starters. 
 
A small KASHTIRA engine is included in Tenpai and it is composed of 1 Wraitsoth, 3 Kashtira Fenrir and 1 Set Rotation. Set Rotation adds another 1 card starter, thus making this strategy slightly more consistent. Fenrir does so much for the deck. In addition to being a very powerful removal juggernaut, Fenrir is capable of searching itself, giving the Tenpai duelist extra discard fodder for Sangen Summoning. That way you can use more staples to OTK rather than fodder for Sangen Summoning or Forbidden Droplet! 
 
The rest of the deck are STAPLES! The board breakers consist of x3 Kashtira Fenrir, x2 Lightning Storm and x1 Harpie's Feather Duster. These board breakers disproportionately eliminate your opponent's resources to make a breakthrough and OTK with Tenpai much easier. There are handtraps aplenty in this deck - so much so that your opponent will most likely have a sub-optimal board facing down your OTK juggernaut. 
 
COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN 
 
The GAMEPLAN with this deck is straightforward – Slowdown your opponent with handtraps, break their board with boardbreakers, then OTK with your 17 1-card starters! The simpler your opponent's gamestate is, the easier it is to OTK.
 
You'll always win the die-roll since you want to go second. Here is the main going-second COMBO for Tenpai Dragon:
 
Sangen Summoning + Discard = 30000+ damage!
 
  1. Activate Sangen Summoning.
  2. Use Sangen Summoning's effect to search Paidra from deck. Discard a card. 
  3. Normal summon Paidra. Search Sangen Kaimen from deck. 
  4. Enter the Battle Phase. Activate Sangen Kaimen to add Chundra from deck to hand then summon it. 
  5. Attack with Chundra. At the start of the damage step, summon Fadra from deck. 
  6. Attack with as many monsters as possible (make at least 3 attacks so that your Extra Deck Tenpai's effects are live).
  7. Activate Chundra's quick synchro effect to synchro summon Sangenpai Bident Dragion using Chundra + Fadra. 
  8. Sangenpai Bident Dragon's on-summon effect to summon from GY Fadra. 
  9. Activate Fadra's effect to summon Chundra from GY. Attack with as many monsters as possible.
  10. Activate Fadra's effect to quick synchro into Trident Dragion using Bident Dragion + Fadra. 
  11. Activate Trident Dragion's on-summon effect to destroy Sangen Summoning and another card you control so it can make 3 attacks.
  12. Activate Sangen Summon's trigger effect in the GY targeting Trident Dragion to double it's attack. 
  13. Attack three times with a 6000 ATK Trident Dragion! As needed, you can summon Bident Dragion from GY to destroy a spell/trap and for additional damage.
 
Obviously, this deck can deviate from the above combo to fit the situation as needed. For example, can use Rose Dragon + Sangen Summoning to destroy everything on the field to clear your opponent's board, then proceed to OTK in the battle phase with your singular Sangen Kaimen. You can also access your synchro toolbox like Meteorburst Dragon to counter specific battle-immune threats like Yubel, Floowandereeze Empen or illusion monsters. 
 
If you haven't finished off your opponent yet, you can link off your remaining Dragons to Hieratic Seals or S:P Little Knight, which are both powerful monsters in a simplified gamestate. Next turn, you can attempt to OTK again! 
 
Congrats duelist, you've most likely cheesed your way to a cheap win in the first match! You can safely assume that most opponents will still try to go first next match, so you're probably good to continue to side in blind second cards. If you feel like your opponent may force you to play 1st, just jam as many handtraps into your deck during siding. 
 
When forced to go first, ending on Hieratic Seals, Fenrir and several handtraps often is enough to stop your opponent in their tracks. Simplifying the gamestate as much as possible is key so that you can still OTK on the crackback next turn. 
 
 
GENERAL TIPS
  • Since this deck contains a ton of handtraps, remember to handtrap your opponents at the most opportune time! Knowing when and where to handtrap is essential to this deck's success since a weakened opponent vastly increases your chances of OTK or FTK. Be sure to study up! 
  • If you can't finish off your opponent with your first OTK attempt with Tenpai, make Seals/S:P with your remaining monsters and maintain your handtraps. You'll likely place your opponent in a simplified gamestate after your onslaught. So a single/couple interruptions is enough to slow them down so you can OTK them again next turn! 
  • If you've been Dimensional Barrier'd, you can always go for the Links instead of Synchros and OTK with Promethean Princess, Salamangreat Raging Phoenix and Zealantis. 
  • If your opponent has handtrapped or floodgated you to a standstill, you can make Striker Dragon then proceed to summon S:P Little Knight to banish one card your opponent controls or in their GY. "S:P pass" with handtraps is as effective as "Seals pass." 
  • Sometimes in games 2/3, your opponent may still go first (perhaps they think you'll use Heatwave or some other kind of floodgate). Worry not! Your Centur-Ion deck has 25 staples/handtraps/boardbreakers to slow down your opponent so you can still play a regular grindgame with their simplified gamestate with the Centur-Ion cards. The only problem 
  • While not optimal, both Tenpai can still OTK under Dimension Shifter. If Shifter is active, damage comes to about 10000, which is borderline OTK if the opponent has some cards on the field. Keep this in mind when playing Shifter, it still hurts your ability to play! 
  • If you're worried about the price of Trident Dragion's hefty $120USD price tag (as of this article's writing), it is not mandatory for the Tenpai strategy. You may not be able to OTK through Prosperity and Shifter however. 9 times out of 10 however, from personal experience I find that games finish with Tenpai before Trident Dragion comes out. 
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 
CONCLUDING REMARKS
 
I admit, I'm not the most "skillful" duelist. I generally don't think 3 turns ahead, play 4 dimensional chess, predict what's in my opponent's hand, etc. That's why I LOVE decks like Tenpai - it makes dueling so easy and simple that even a "Yugi-Boomer" like me can win against meta! I've always been a player who loves "aggro" playstyles and I find it sooo unbelievably satisfying dismantling boards and control decks. Naturally, a blind second meta deck is the perfect deck for me (and perhaps for you as well)! 
 
Players are sure to catch on to this "cheesy" style of dueling so it's competitive viability might not be around for long. The more people are ready to side and play against Tenpai, the less effective the strategy may be. Perhaps Tenpai may be so unstoppable and annoying that Konami themselves have to step in and outright limit/ban the cards! In the meantime while the deck is at the zenith of it's power... Lets enjoy our free wins with Tenpai Dragon! 😉 
 
GLHF Duelists!

deck_name: The Vibrant and Chaotic Ecosystem of Turtle Island
deck_description:
The Vibrant and Chaotic Ecosystem of Turtle Island

Introduction

On the expansive back of Turtle Island {4042268}, an ancient turtle whose shell is covered in a lush, sprawling forest, towering mountains, and a few sacred temples, a vibrant and chaotic ecosystem thrives. This colossal turtle, larger than most countries, swims leisurely under the hot sun. Its back hosts a myriad of creatures, from beasts and monsters to demons and fiends, all engaged in their perpetual struggles, whether flying through the air or clashing on the ground.

The Respite and the Upheaval

As the turtle swam, it eventually found a piece of land similar to itself, adorned with trees and foliage. Relieved to find respite from the scorching sun, the turtle settled under a large tree, sighing in contentment. However, this movement caused a significant disturbance on its back, shaking the land and causing turmoil among its many inhabitants. The creatures, including those central to our story, found themselves abruptly disrupted by this unexpected tremor.

The Ancient Temple and Its Guardians

Haniwa: The Vigilant Sentinel

At the heart of Turtle Island stands an ancient temple, constructed long ago by wise beasts. This temple is guarded by Haniwa {84285623}, a vigilant sentinel, who stands watch over the sanctuary of an ancient wood spirit. Observing the recent upheaval, Haniwa thought with concern, "Great, another shaking. This is going to wake up the creature slumbering inside."

Inpachi and Hinotama Soul: The Awakening

Within the temple, Inpachi {97923414}, a formidable creature made of wood, had been in a deep slumber. As flames began to flicker outside the temple, Hinotama Soul {96851799}, a fiery spirit, charged recklessly into the temple, colliding with Inpachi and setting him ablaze. The once dormant wooden creature was now engulfed in flames, illuminating the shadowy area with an eerie glow.

The Chaos Unfolds

Kattapillar and Flame Viper: The Heat

Kattapillar {81179446}, a caterpillar-like creature, began to sweat profusely from the intense heat. Seeking refuge, it scurried back to the tree where it had been resting. Meanwhile, a Flame Viper {2830619}, intrigued by the sight of the blazing Inpachi, attempted to intensify the flames by spitting fire. However, this only caused Inpachi to flinch momentarily before swinging its fiery log-like arms in retaliation. The viper quickly retreated, burrowing back into its hole to escape the searing heat.

M-Warrior #1: The Brave Warrior

The commotion did not go unnoticed. The sounds emanating from the blazing Inpachi attracted the attention of M-Warrior #1 {56342351}, a formidable creature known for its strength and bravery. After his initial rage, he noticed the shaking of Turtle Island and heard the tumultuous sounds that followed. Sensing the disturbance, M-Warrior #1 began to make his way towards the source of the flames, prepared to confront whatever threat might be emerging from the chaos.

The Sky and the Mountains

Thunder Dragons: The Aerial Guardians

A group of Thunder Dragons {31786629}, sensing the disturbance, took to the skies, their roars echoing across the land. They circled above, crackling with electric energy, ready to strike if the need arose.

Wolf Axwielder and Silver Fang: The Snowy Sanctuary

In the snowy mountains on the turtle's back, Wolf Axwielder {56369281} was on a mission to protect Silver Fang {90357090}. The tremors disrupted their journey, prompting Wolf Axwielder to ready his axe, prepared for any threat that might approach their snowy sanctuary.

The Dark and the Curious

Ryu-Kishin: The Demonic Lurker

Elsewhere on the island, a Ryu-Kishin {15303296)} lurked in a cave on the side of a mountain. This demonic creature, disturbed by the quakes, emerged from its lair, its eyes glowing ominously as it sensed the growing chaos outside.

Sky Scout and Whiptail Crow: The Observers

High above in the treetops, a Sky Scout {30532390} watched the unfolding events with sharp eyes. This agile creature, always alert, prepared to swoop down and assist if the battle below required aerial support. Noticing the Sky Scout, a Whiptail Crow {91996584} decided to fly towards it, curious about the scout's intentions and the events transpiring below.

The Fiery Clash

M-Warrior #1 vs. Fire Kraken

As M-Warrior #1 advanced, he encountered a Fire Kraken {46534755} emerging from a nearby lake. The Kraken, drawn by the fire and the promise of a fight, raised its tentacles menacingly. Undeterred, M-Warrior #1 {56342351} brandished his weapon, ready to face the fiery beast.

The Melancholic Observer

Big Koala: The Serene Giant

Elsewhere, a Big Koala {42129512} sat quietly in the shade of a giant eucalyptus tree, a pair of headphones over its ears. It was listening to depressing lofi music, the melancholic beats resonating deeply within. A tear rolled down the koala's cheek as it sensed the turmoil brewing across Turtle Island. The normally serene creature felt a pang of sadness, knowing that a great conflict was about to unfold.

Conclusion

In this vibrant and dangerous ecosystem, the balance was fragile, and every creature played a part in maintaining or disrupting it. The outcome of the impending confrontations would determine the fate of those who called Turtle Island their home. The intricate web of interactions among the creatures of Turtle Island illustrates the delicate harmony and constant struggle that defines life on this colossal, living world.

deck_excerpt: Rank 8's and Horus monsters, Level 5/7 and occasionally 8 Synchros alongside Triamid Field Spell loop to Triamid Sphinx
deck_description:
The Triamid and Adamancipator half of this deck is nearly the same as this deck https://ygoprodeck.com/deck/triamid-321377 ; However we are not playing Doki-Doki or the Koa'ki engine.

This deck is more Triamid than Horus or Adamancipator. Only play this deck if you enjoy Triamid and would like to use them.

Rank 8's and Horus monsters, Level 5/7 and occasionally 8 Synchros alongside Triamid Field Spell loop to Triamid Sphinx

Use Ancient Fairy Dragon to give you access to Triamid Hunter through Triamid Cruiser. You can also access the Horus engine through Walls of the Imperial Tomb by destroying a Triamid field spell.

 Garden Rose Flora has synergy with Triamid Field spells, triggering their effects when sent to the graveyard. This can search with Triamid Cruiser when you otherwise cannot get it into the graveyard. You can then go into a Level 7 Synchro with the Token summoned by Flora.

A nice interaction this deck has is summoning Black Rose Dragon while Dingirsu, the Orcust of the Evening Star is on your field. This provides a one-sided board wipe as Dingirsu detaches to protect your field. You can get to this from Garden Rose Flora as well as directly with Adamancipator Analyzer

Ideally, your Level 5 Synchro will be Naturia Beast, if you hard drew into your Field Spells and do not need to use Garden Rose Flora.

 Triamid Pulse is an extremely valuable trap. Use it to destroy your opponents face-up cards, as well as special summon needed Adamancipator or Triamid monsters from the Graveyard.

Playing with this deck in Master Duel, working out changes. It certainly feels better to play than without the Horus cards. The deck can run into hand resource issues with the need to reduce hand size from Imsety, Glory of Horus, King's Sarcophagus, and Walls of the Imperial Tomb. There may be situations where you have to forego Triamid/Adamancipator plays to use the Horus cards and vice-versa.
