deck_excerpt: Ancient Egypt + Japanese Cyberpunk = COOL AND POWERFUL DECK!
deck_description:
Masterduel Selection Pack Revived Legion has premiered the "Horus" archetype that provides PUNK a much needed power boost in the form of many level 8 bodies on board! The Horus quartet of Imsety, Duamutef, Hapi and Qebehsenuef enable PUNK to do pretty insane plays! Cyberpunk aesthetic combines with Ancient Egyptian motifs to form a visually amazing and powerfully fun rogue deck!
 
Horus allows PUNK to play through handtraps especially Droll, since King's Sarcophagus sends Horus card to the GY rather than adding them to the hand.  If your PUNK deck was stopped by too much interruption, you can pivot to the Horus engine instead! The extra bodies on board and the level 8s for synchro/XYZ/link summons allow PUNK to draw up to 6 cards per turn and summon double Psychic End Punisher! If you haven't been lucky enough to draw into one of your 15 one card PUNK starters, Zombie Vampire Coach King Giantrainer made with the level 8s that Horus provides also gives you another chance to get your starter! The PUNK duelist can also end of a board of Sharakusai (for Amazing Dragon), I:P Masquerena (for S:P Little Knight), and Nashiwari Surprise (1 pop) while drawing 6 cards! 
 
While not the strongest deck on Masterduel ladder, Horus certainly gives PUNK a much needed power boost to enable it to compete toe to toe with meta heavyweights like Snake-Eyes and Branded. 
 
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 
ARCHETYPES AND DECKBUILDING
 
In contrast to other iterations of this PUNK, I prefer a sizeable PUNK deck consisting of 55 cards. It is 55 cards since one Ze Amin + discard is full PUNK combo, and there are 15 copies of Ze Amin (3 Ze Amin, 3 Ogre, 3 Foxy Tune, 3 Emergency Teleport and 3 Small World) giving the duelist a fair chance of drawing into it with their starting hand. 55 cards also make it less likely that you will hard draw your garnets (Sharakusai, Deer Note, Wa Gon and Jam Session) that are essential for the combo. Trust me, 55 cards is still surprisingly consistent and totally not bricky, especially since you can draw up to 4 cards with the Horus engine!
 
The two archetypes in this deck are of course PUNK (16 cards) and Horus (9 cards). PUNK cards are your starters for the main combo while Horus are extenders that enhance your board while obtaining more resources.
 
The usual "Maxx C" package is included with 1 Crossout, 2 Called By the Grave, 3 Ash Blossom and 3 Maxx C. The Gamma packahe also is there to counter Maxx C and any other handtraps with 2 Gamma and 1 Driver. The rest of the handtrap staples are included as Small World bridges to search your starters. 
 
COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN
 
The strategy of PUNK Horus is to interrupt your opponent as much as possible while building as much resource advantage as you can with multiple draws and searches. The turn after, if your opponent hasn't surrendered yet, both Horus and PUNK have massive follow-up to enable an easy OTK. If King's Sarcophagus is intact until the next turn, your opponent will have to contend with 4 giant beatsticks summoned basically for free! The PUNK cards have follow-up to, since Jam Session and Amazing Dragon is on the field and Dragon Drive is in the GY. Both engines can OTK independently!
 
The combo for this strategy is the standard PUNK combo -> Horus combo. Here is the main combo for PUNK Horus: 
 
PUNK Ze Amin + Horus Imsety + 2 discards = Draw 6 cards (several handtraps in hand) + I:P Masquerena (S:P Little Knight's x2 banish) + Horus Monsters and Sharakusai (Amazing Dragon's x4 bounce) + PUNK Trap (1 pop/negate) + King's Sarcophagus with Horus in GY (Follow-up)  
  1. (The following is standard PUNK combo) Summon Ze Amin. Ze Amin searches for Foxy Tune. 
  2. Foxy Tune effect to discard 1 card in hand to summon Sharakusai from deck. 
  3. Sharakusai fusion summons Rising Carp, using Sharakusai + Ze Amin. 
  4. Tribute Rising Carp to summon Deer Note and Wa Gon from deck. 
  5. Activate Wa Gon's effect to search for Jam Session from deck. 
  6. Activate Jam Session. 
  7. Synchro summon Dragon Drive using Wa Gon + Deer Note. 
  8. CL1 Dragon Drive to search for Madame Spider from deck, CL2 Deer Note to summon Sharakusai from GY. 
  9. Jam Session's trigger effect draws you 1 card. 
  10. Special summon Madam Spider from hand using Jam Session. Madame Spider searches for PUNK trap (I prefer Nashiwari Surprise targeted pop for this current meta) from deck. 
  11. Jam Session's trigger effect draws you 1 card a second time. 
  12. (The following is the Horus combo) Activate Imsety Horus' effect in hand to search for King's Sarcophagus and draw 1 card.
  13. Activate King's Sarcophagus.
  14. Activate King's Sarcophagus' effect to send one card from your hand to the GY to send a Horus monster to the GY (A Horus name that already isn't in the GY).
  15. Summon Imsety from the GY and another Horus monster since you control King's Sarcophagus.
  16. XYZ summon Coach King Giantrainer using 2 Horus monsters + Dragon Drive.
  17. Draw 3 cards with Coach King Giantrainer, activating it's effect 3 times.
  18. Activate King's Sarcophagus' effect twice more to send the rest of the Horus monsters from deck to GY.
  19. Summon the two Horus monsters from the GY since you control King's Sarcophagus. (Preferably you keep Duamutef and Hapi on the field, since they both float if any of your cards are removed from field).
  20. Link away Madame Spider + Coach King Giantrainer for I:P Masqurena. (Alternatively if you have an extender, you can Synchro Madame Spider + Horus monster for End Punisher, while you Link away Giantrainer + extender for S:P Little Knight. This is a beefier board)
  21. Set the rest of your spells/traps, especially the PUNK trap that was searched earlier.
With Ze Amin + Imsety + 2 discards, you get many interruptions and resources! The PUNK duelist gets a draw 6 (many cards are handtraps/interruptions), S:P Little Knight's double banish, Amazing Dragon's x4 bounce + 1 draw with Jam Session, and a set PUNK trap! This is the ultimate combo available for PUNK Horus, but chances are, you aren't going to achieve this board because of handtraps being very commonplace during this meta. 
 
Even if you're board wiped, Horus Hapi would recover two cards from the GY/Banished for follow-up or interruption. Also, if you're board wiped S:P Little Knight can save your monsters by banishing them until the endphase so you can keep your board for next turn! 
 
You'll generally have 5+ cards in hand if you're allowed to full combo, so you'll have plenty of handtraps and follow-up.
 
Technically, the combo can draw up to 7 cards since you can draw 1 more card on your opponent's turn with Sharakusai's quick synchro as well.
 
If you're interrupted mid-combo by a turn-ending card, your plan B is to summon Psychic End Punisher to stall for next turn's counterattack, since most decks cannot out it easily. 
 
Generally, a fully set-up Horus engine in the GY with King's Sarcophagus on the field flattens every single deck/board during your counterattack on turn 3 since all the Horus monsters are gigantic beatsticks backed by King Sarcophagus' powerful battlephase removal. 
 
Going second, hopefully your handtraps simplify the gamestate enough to the point your in-engine combo and extenders are enough to allow you to play the game through your opponent's interruption. Triple Tactics Thrust can also fetch you much needed board breakers like Evenly Matched to obliterate your opponent's board so you can combo off in Main Phase 2. 
 
The PUNK Horus pilot has a plethora of options to clear the board and OTK going second based on the gamestate: 
 
 A 4 material Zeus is easily summoned with 2 level 3s -> Fortune Tune -> Battle Phase attack -> Downerd ->  Zeus. a 4 Material Zeus can also be summoned with 2 level 8s -> Dingirsu (send card to GY) -> Battle Phase attack -> Pain Gainer -> Zeus.
 
If you have Imsety/King's Sarcophagus in-hand, you can activate King's Sarc 4 times to set up your Horus engine in the GY. Summon all 4 Horus monsters and that's 12700ATK on board while King's Sarc sends a monster to the GY!
 
1 Ze Amin + 1 discard can make Amazing Dragon synchro summoned with Rising Carp + Ze Amin clears 2-4 cards from the board while enabling it to attack twice with 3600ATK accompanied with Dragon Drive (2700ATK) totalling 9900 ATK! 
 
PUNK Ze Amin + 1 discard = 3600ATK Amazing Dragon that can attack twice, bounce 4 cards your opponent controls with Amazing Dragon, 2700 ATK Dragon Drive.
  1. (The following is standard PUNK combo) Summon Ze Amin. Ze Amin searches for Foxy Tune. 
  2. Foxy Tune effect to discard 1 card in hand to summon Sharakusai from deck. 
  3. Sharakusai fusion summons Rising Carp, using Sharakusai + Ze Amin. 
  4. Tribute Rising Carp to summon Deer Note and Wa Gon from deck. 
  5. Activate Wa Gon's effect to search for Jam Session from deck. 
  6. Activate Jam Session. 
  7. Synchro summon Dragon Drive using Wa Gon + Deer Note. 
  8. CL1 Dragon Drive to search for Ze Amin from deck, CL2 Deer Note to summon Rising Carp from GY. 
  9. Jam Session's trigger effect draws you 1 card. 
  10. Special summon Ze Amin from hand using Jam Session.
  11. Synchro Summon Amazing Dragon using Ze Amin + Rising Carp.
  12. CL1 Amazing Dragon to bounce up to 4 cards your opponent controls, CL2 Rising Carp targeting Amazing Dragon enabling it to attack twice, CL3 Ze Amin targeting Amazing Dragon boosting it's ATK by 600.
GENERAL TIPS
  • If you get hit by Droll & Lockbird, Dimension Shifter, or even Maxx "C," your typical plan B is to synchro summon Psychic End Punisher. Chances are that your opponent cannot out this monster and you'll be alive next turn to continue counterattack without committing too much of your resources.
  • This deck absolutely sucks vs. backrow floodgates or backrow, meaning that the common Stun decks and Labrynth duelists absolutely body this deck. Thankfully, Triple Tactics Thrust can search Evenly Matched.
  • Not only does Small World search Ze Amin to start your combo, it also for your Horus engine! From my experience nobody really negates Small World since they'd rather negate a choke point in a combo, so Small World is a great card to open with so you can start clearing your opponent's board.
  • Photon Lord is an excellent card to help insulate your PUNK combo from monster-based interruptions, especially handtraps. If you can make Photon Lord before starting your PUNK combo, do it to ensure the success of your PUNK plays. 
  • PUNK Horus can pivot into other playstyles of one aspect of the game has been floodgated to you. Has the opponent resolved D-Barrier calling out Synchros? You can play with XYZs instead! Has your PUNK combo been stopped in it's tracks? Use the Horus engine! 
  • If you don't have access to your PUNK starters and you have the Horus engine available, you can draw 3 with Coach King Giantrainer. There is a high chance that you'll draw into one of the the 15 copies of Ze Amin in your deck! You can also summon Zombie Vampire with 2 Horus monsters to potentially summon a starter from your mills. 
  • The Zombie Vampire is also another viable extender and luck based "searcher" in this deck. Simply XYZ summon him with 2 Horus monsters, activate effect to mill 4, and you may likely find a PUNK starter! Later on in the combo, Zombie Vampire can be linked away into S:P Little Knight with her on-summon banish effect active. 
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 
CONCLUDING REMARKS
 
Ever since I've picked up the PUNK deck when Grand Creators came out January 2022 - I've been a total fan of this strategy, playstyle and aesthetic of the deck. With Horus, not only does the Egyptian aesthetic makes the deck look cooler, PUNK's powerlevels have received another boost with all the level 8 bodies it has access to! Drawing 6+ cards and ending on a full PUNK board is a gamestate most duelists would have difficulty dealing with, making PUNK stronger than ever!
 
Now, this strategy is available in Masterduel! It may not be the strongest deck in the cutthroat meta ladder, but it is still a potent threat that any strategy would be hard pressed to face, especially if allowed to go first!
 
GLHF Duelists!

deck_name: Storms and Spirits: Legends of the Turtle Island
deck_description:
Storms and Spirits: Legends of the Turtle Island

While the turtle rested beneath the sheltering canopy of the sprawling forest that bordered the edge of its domain, the rest of the world lay mostly submerged beneath vast oceans. The land upon which the turtle resided covered a significant third of the world's surface, serving as a sanctuary for myriad creatures.

Meanwhile, towering cities thrived at the heart of this land, bustling hubs of activity and civilization. Yet, on the fringes, where the turtle found solace under the protective embrace of the forest, life unfolded in a different rhythm, intimately connected with the ebb and flow of nature.



As the turtle nestled under the shade of the towering trees that dotted its vast habitat, a distant rumble echoed through the sky. Above, thunder dragons stirred, casting dark clouds across the turtle's back.

Seeking refuge from the scorching sun, the turtle felt the stirrings of the storm brewing around it, the promise of rain and snow teasing the air. Yet, amidst the tempest, the turtle found solace in the sporadic bursts of coolness against its shell.

With a contented sigh, the turtle embraced the gentle chaos, drawing energy from the elemental dance unfolding above. For even as the storm raged, it brought life and vitality to the world upon its back, a reminder of the interconnectedness of all things in the grand tapestry of nature.

As the thunder dragons soared overhead, their massive forms circling the snow-capped peaks of the mountains, storms erupted across the entire island. Dark clouds gathered, crackling with lightning and rumbling with thunder, casting an ominous shadow over the landscape below.

Worry gripped the hearts of all creatures as they sought shelter from the impending tempest. Amidst the chaos, Silver Fang, a mighty and revered leader among his kind, sensed the looming danger. With swift determination, he bounded towards the mountains where his den lay nestled amidst the snow.

Three loyal Wolf Axwielders, guardians of Silver Fang's domain, watched with unwavering resolve as their faithful maven approached. Their keen eyes scanned the horizon, alert to any signs of danger. Above, the thunder dragons circled relentlessly, their presence casting a pall of fear over the land.

As Silver Fang reached the safety of his den, the Wolf Axwielders sprang into action, preparing to defend their home and their beloved leader. With bared fangs and steely determination, they stood ready to face whatever threats may come, their loyalty unwavering in the face of adversity

After impaling Petit Angel; M-warrior #1, fueled by his own anger and the oppressive heat that enveloped him, let out a primal yell into the tumultuous sky. The shaking of the turtle island, a consequence of the turtle's movements, served as a stark reminder of the shifting balance of the world.

Despite the searing heat, M-warrior #1's thoughts drifted back to his struggles in the city, where bitter cold had been his constant companion. He shivered uncontrollably, memories of frostbitten nights and empty stomachs haunting his every step.

For M-warrior #1, the city had been both a sanctuary and a prison, a place of lost dreams and shattered hopes. Raised amidst the bustle and clamor of urban life, he had yearned for strength and purpose, driven by the memories of his family's struggles and the tales of their attempts to find common ground.

As M-warrior #1 continued his journey across the sweltering expanse of the turtle's back, the flickering flames from the burning trees caught his eye, casting an eerie glow against the darkening sky. Memories of his companion, M-warrior #2, flooded his mind, a stark contrast to his own struggles and hardships.

M-warrior #2, born into privilege and luxury, had known a life of abundance and comfort, his wealth and status shielding him from the harsh realities of the world. Yet, even he had not been immune to the ravages of chaos and destruction, his lands ravaged by the merciless hands of bandits.

Despite their differences, M-warrior #1 and M-warrior #2 had forged a bond born of shared experiences and common goals. United in their quest for power and purpose, they had set out together in search of adventure and opportunity, their paths converging amidst the chaos of the turtle's back.

Now, as the flames danced before him, M-warrior #1 felt a renewed sense of determination coursing through his veins. With each step forward, he drew closer to his destiny, fueled by the flames of determination that burned bright within his heart.

As the Whiptail Crow swooped down, its sharp tail aimed at the Sky Scout, a master of the skies, the tension in the air was palpable. But the Sky Scout, with lightning reflexes, anticipated the attack and swiftly dodged, narrowly avoiding the lethal strike.

With a graceful maneuver, the Sky Scout countered with blinding speed, striking the Whiptail Crow with such force that it left deep scars on its feathers. The Whiptail cried out in pain, its wings flapping frantically as it struggled to escape the onslaught.

Despite its injuries, the Whiptail managed to flee, retreating to the safety of its nest somewhere on the sprawling expanse of the turtle's back. And as the Sky Scout watched the Whiptail disappear into the distance, it knew that victory was its own, a testament to its skill and prowess in the unforgiving skies.

With a satisfied chirp, the Sky Scout soared gracefully into the azure sky, its feathers glinting in the sunlight as it continued its endless journey across the vast expanse of the turtle's back.

As the Sky Scout basked in the glory of its victory, a sense of duty beckoned it back to the heart of the turtle's domain. With a graceful swoop, it soared higher into the sky, the wind whispering secrets as it ascended.

Guided by an unseen force, the Sky Scout veered towards the majestic head of the turtle, where ancient wisdom and boundless power resided. For the Sky Scout was not merely a creature of the skies but a faithful servant, entrusted with the sacred task of safeguarding the turtle and its inhabitants.

With each beat of its wings, the Sky Scout drew closer to its destination, the air crackling with anticipation. And as it alighted upon the turtle's head, a sense of reverence washed over it, a humble servant in the presence of greatness.

For the Sky Scout knew that its purpose was intertwined with the fate of the turtle and all who called it home. And as it gazed out over the vast expanse of land and sea, it vowed to continue its vigilant watch, ever faithful to the ancient bond that bound it to the turtle's destiny.

As the Sky Scout perched upon the turtle's head, a sense of urgency gripped them both. For beneath the canopy of the forest, the ancient burning wood spirits, Inpachi, had awoken from their slumber, their fiery wrath scorching the lands in their wake.

The realization of their awakening filled the air with a palpable tension, as the Sky Scout and the turtle exchanged worried glances. The burning wood spirits, older than even the mighty turtle, posed a threat unlike any other, their flames consuming everything in their path with relentless fury.

With a shared sense of determination, the Sky Scout and the turtle knew that they must act swiftly to quell the inferno before it consumed the entire island. For the fate of their home hung in the balance, and only by working together could they hope to overcome this ancient menace.

This was an extra endding may the true ending yet to unfold!

As the raging inferno threatened to engulf the island, a new player emerged onto the scene, the big koala, a legendary guardian known for its immense strength and unwavering courage. With a thunderous roar, it bounded into the fray, Orcust Cymbal Skeleton {21441617} in hand, ready to make its mark on the unfolding tale.

With a flourish, the big koala struck a final chord on its instrument, signaling the end of the chaos that had gripped the land. Orcust Cymbal Skeleton's note reverberated through the air, a powerful declaration that the story had reached its conclusion.

As the flames dimmed and the smoke cleared, a sense of peace descended upon the island once more. The Sky Scout, the turtle, and the big koala stood together, their combined efforts bringing an end to the threat posed by the ancient burning wood spirits.

With a nod of gratitude and respect, the big koala bid farewell to its companions, disappearing back into the forest from whence it came. And as Orcust Cymbal Skeleton's final note echoed into the distance, the Sky Scout took to the skies, the turtle resumed its peaceful slumber, and the island returned to a state of tranquility.

 

For though the journey had been perilous, and the challenges great, the bond forged between these unlikely allies had proven stronger than any obstacle they faced. And as they went their separate ways, they carried with them the memories of their shared adventure, and the knowledge that together, they had achieved the impossible.

deck_excerpt: Generaider, Superheavy Samurai, World legacy, World Chalice
deck_description:
Just a new fun way to play Generaider with max consistency compared to other builds.

The deck has 3 one card starters that can end on some nasty boards being : Wakauchi , Bike and Metalcruncher.

So the combo starts by scaling Wakauchi , scaling benkei , searching for helmet , equip helmet and special summon it , then you go into Ibb in the extra monster zone (important) search world legacy Monstrosity , link Ibb for gravity controller , Ibb effect to summon lee and search Chosen by the world chalice. pend summon it or normal (your choice) , then Banish Gravity controller , lee and chosen to bring Trishula then activate monstrosity summon ,Harr and Mardel , Search boss stage with Mardel and activate it , Overlay Mardel and Trishula for Jormangander , activate Jormangander effect detaching Mardel , Boss stage triggers and So Harr to hand loop your opponent for one , boss stage summon Vala which will bring back Mardel, Overlay Mardel and Vala for Hypertron and if you started the combo with Metal cruncher or any monster that you can pend summon you can use it and Harr for I:P Masquerina. During the next draw phase you summon Vala to bring back Harr from grave and in standby u use Jormngander again and trigger Harr to hand loop him for another card and if you have to draw into droll or open it even better you can lock them right there and then without them even getting to searchanything for the rest of the turn. So one card can handloop for 2 , having an 2 negates ,  I:P into an S:P and follow up for days. 

The deck is also well equipped going second because of the 12 handtraps and Levaitan being also so great in breaking boards and paving the way for a big fat Zeus and if it happens that I open combo it can be a good plan B. Ty-phon has great synergy with the deck if u only have boss stage so you can summon it with anything. pick the board as best as you can and then drop boss stage. Zoodiacs in the side deck are honestly experimental but they're good if you need to push through interruptions at the very least and breaking giant boards and katarooster can be great because it can contest S:p and Promethean Princess. Speaking of , Princess is also very good as a game closer and can be very useful for grind games to bring back Vala or Otk out of no where.


Metalcruncher is the best starter of the deck, Not only because he can search bike to full combo from there but he's also a level 9 which makes him a target for world legacy monstrosity, plus the deck doesn't use a normal summon so it's a seamless fit into the deck.

Yes the deck can play shifter but the combo lines become a bit different so u don't lose resources that's why I prefer it on the side for certain matchups.

deck_description:
(Check attached Youtube Video)

DOMAIN FORMAT

60 Main Deck

up to 15 extra deck

Any monster as your deckmaster (with balanced rules)

Deckmaster determines which Types/Attributes/Named Archetype monsters you can play

Nothing is banned

Singleton

Played in 4 player pods

 

My friends and I play Domain Format in Discord. Others have compared it to the MTG Commander format.

Anyone can come ask questions or learn the format to build a deck. https://discord.gg/GxXHC4qCYM
The trail of cryptids lead to Dark World

Darklord Control Deck: Dominate with Banishment!

This deck focuses on controlling the duel through targeted banishment and disruption. Here's the breakdown:

Monsters (24):

  • Darklord Engine (13): The core of the deck. Ixchel searches for Darklords, Superbia special summons itself from the hand, Nergal banishes your opponent's monsters, and Indulged Darklord brings back banished Darklords. Ukoback is a solid beater and Amdusc/Nasten have situational effects.
  • Hand Traps (6): Ash Blossom and Infinite Impermanence are staples for stopping your opponent's plays.
  • Utility (5): Allure of Darkness thins your deck for consistency, Trade-In gets Darklords to the graveyard, Metalfoes Fusion provides an unexpected Fusion play, and Called by the Grave disrupts your opponent's graveyard.

Spells (14):

  • Darklord Support (6): Darklord Contact banishes your opponent's monster for a Darklord summon, Foolish Burial puts a Darklord in the graveyard for later plays, Banishment of the Darklords searches or banishes Darklords, and Darklord Rebellion/Uprising offer powerful comeback effects.
  • General Support (8): Super Polymerization removes problem monsters, Infinite Impermanence provides additional hand trap disruption.

Extra Deck (14):

  • Darklord Links (2): The First Darklord is your boss monster, offering negation and revival.
  • Fusion Monsters (4): Starving Venom Fusion Dragon steals ATK, Garura helps with Synchro plays, Mudragon searches banished DARK monsters, and Number 97: Draglubion offers removal.
  • Rank 8/9 (3): Number 38: Hope Harbinger Dragon Titanic Galaxy is a powerful negate, Dingirsu offers monster and spell/trap negation.
  • Rank 4/Xyz (3): Number 100: Numeron Dragon is a big beater, Underworld Goddess is a banish effect, Apollousa is a negate arrow monster.
  • Knightmare Unicorn and S:P Little Knight offer generic removal.
  • Condemned Darklord provides a Link 2 option for the Darklord engine.

Overall Strategy:

  • Use hand traps and Called by the Grave to disrupt your opponent's plays.
  • Banish your opponent's monsters with Darklord effects and Super Polymerization.
  • Summon Darklords like Ixchel, Superbia, and Indulged Darklord to gain advantage.
  • Link climb into The First Darklord for powerful negation and revival.
  • Utilize the versatile Extra Deck for specific situations.

This deck prioritizes control and resource denial. It can be adapted with different tech choices and Extra Deck monsters to fit your playstyle and the current metagame.

deck_excerpt: Salamangreat  / DNDA New Era Championship Summer 2024 1st Place
deck_description:
Category: Tournament Meta Decks (Asian-English OCG)

Tournament Meta Decks are current-level Meta Decks that are capable of going up against the best of the best. These are curated lists that cannot be uploaded by regular users.

Creator: Lê Nguyễn An Sinh

Tournament: DNDA New Era Championship Summer 2024 – May 26th 2024

Placement: 1st Place

Fire King Burn with Control Elements

This Yu-Gi-Oh! deck focuses on utilizing the burning power of Fire King monsters to overwhelm your opponent's life points. Here's a breakdown of its strategy:

Core Engine:

  • Fire King Monsters: The deck revolves around Fire King cards like Sacred Fire King Garunix and Fire King High Avatar Kirin. Their effects deal burn damage and help control the field by destroying your opponent's monsters.
  • Fire King Spells and Traps: Fire King Sanctuary and Fire King Island boost your Fire King monsters and activate additional burn effects. Bonfire and Fire King Sky Burn inflict further damage directly to your opponent's life points.

Support Cards:

  • Burn Enablers: Neo Flamvell Lady and Blaster, Dragon Ruler of Infernos raise your own life points to activate Fire King effects. Called by the Grave helps to retrieve banished Fire King monsters for further plays.
  • Hand Traps & Disruption: Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring, Ghost Ogre & Snow Rabbit, and Effect Veiler stop your opponent's key plays, allowing you to maintain control.
  • Monster Removal: Dogoran, the Mad Flame Kaiju and Solemn Judgment offer strong removal options for troublesome monsters.

Extra Deck:

  • Generic XYZ & Link Monsters: This deck offers a toolbox Extra Deck with various Link and XYZ monsters like Dingirsu, the Orcust of the Evening Star and S:P Little Knight to handle different situations during the duel.
  • Burn & Control Options: Garunix Eternity, Hyang of the Fire Kings provides additional burn damage, while Underworld Goddess of the Closed World disrupts your opponent's graveyard plays.

Overall Playstyle:

This deck aims to control the field with Fire King effects and hand traps while building your life points. Once in a strong position, unleash burn damage through Fire King effects, Spells, and Traps to take down your opponent.

Weaknesses:

  • Reliance on Fire King effects: If your opponent manages to negate your Fire King activations, your burn strategy can falter.
  • Vulnerability to mass removal: Decks with heavy monster removal can disrupt your Fire King setup.

Side Deck Options:

Consider including cards that counter specific deck types you expect to face in the side deck to further optimize your strategy.

deck_excerpt: Please use You're finished I'm begging
deck_description: Something I've been playing around with for a while, decided to finally upload. The horus engine helps out greatly here and is almost essential for most of your plays. 3 BBS can be bricky, but it usually isn't a problem. Cut it down to 2 if you'd like, but I will hate you and hunt you down..... An ideal starting hand would have Diabellstar, Imsety and Malicious, they alone will help you do most of your plays. If you don't start off with this opening hand, it can usually be saved unless you brick, in this case you should consider quitting yugioh, bricking is your choice after all and you're a failure for making it. As long as you can get zombie vampire out, or a hand with a few useful trap monsters, stuff may work out. You're finished has always been a card I've been fond of, never was bad or hard to pull off, people are just mean. You'll get her to go off quite easily, especially in this deck if you've got BBS active. A basic play you wanna go for here is trying to make cupid pitch, lower its level and if malicious is on the field, go into crocodragon, draw from crocodragon then use pitch's graveyard effect to fetch corridor, activate corridor then go into Colossus. If malicious isn't on the field, that's fine, other synchros are there to help with other levels but it isn't ideal. The ishizu cards and Prima Donna will help at least a lil with recursion if there's things in your grave you don't want in there. Oddly fun lil deck I like messing around with, enjoy and say sorry to You're Finished

deck_excerpt: Control, then put the opponent to sleep.

deck_description:
A dragonmaid deck utilizing Laundry to her fullest to mill Paleozoic monsters alongside traps which love being in the graveyard.

This deck is surprisingly self synergistic, with dragonmaids having their own normal trap, which loves being in the graveyard thanks to marella; laundry and nurse making perfect xyz materials and the big dragons essentially making dinomischys having no cost.

At it's worst, you get chamber > search tidying > set 5 pass. At it's best, you plus infinity.

I've been using this deck to climb the ladder and it has gotten me to diamond, thanks to it's incredible grind game and disruption which a lot of decks have a hard time dealing with (and rise to full height targeting a small dragonmaid you bounce, makes battle phase irrelevant for your opponent).

It's my favorite deck and I hope some more people will try and enjoy it too!

deck_excerpt: What's the most you can make when you Normal Summon Machina Gearframe?
deck_description:
This is an updated version of a previous list that is my ongoing project to document my insanity.

 

It all started with a question: "What's the most you can make when you Normal Summon Machina Gearframe?"

 

Today I have a new answer.

 

Full disclosure, the list is not optimal, it runs a number of bricks and garnets and can definitely go over 40 cards, sacrelige though that may be. This is just all the cards necessary for the silly little combo I've been working on, plus a suite of hand traps that I like right now.

 

Anyway. on to the combo.

Opening hand: 1x Machina Gearframe (or 1x Superheavy Samurai Motorbike, or 1x Superheavy Samurai Wakaushi).

I'll abbreviate from here, try to keep up.

1. NS Gearframe, search Unclaspare, Unclaspare SS itself, Unclaspare mill Ruinforce.

2. Overlay for Gigant, detach to search Bike, pitch Bike to search Wakaushi, activate Wakaushi, Wakaushi effect to SS itself and place Benkei, Benkei search Gaia, Gaia equip to Wakaushi, Gaia SS itself. This is the end of phase 1, where most combos starting with these cards will end up.

3. Overlay for Gigant, detach to search Guitaar, Link both Gigants for Ballista, Ballista search Box (that's where the cat goes), Box search Trencher. Banish Unclaspare, Wakaushi and Gaia to SS Ruinforce, Link Ballista and Ruinforce for Genius.

4. Activate Guitaar, Pendulum Summon Box + Trencher to Genius' zones, trigger Genius to search Regulus. Regulus SS itself and equip Gearframe, Gearframe SS itself. Overlay Box + Gearframe for Gigant, detach to search Harvester.

5. Guitaar pitch Harvester to summon Miccs (you can now Normal Summon an additional time this turn), overlay Miccs + Trencher for River Stormer (to a zone Genius *doesn't* point to), detach Trencher to search Gearframe. Banish Trencher to revive Harvester, Harvester search Tunneler, tribute Gigant to SS Tunneler, Harvester target Tunneler to make them both 7, overlay for Dracossack (again, to a zone Genius *doesn't* point to) Dracossack detach Tunneler to summon tokens to Genius' zones, trigger Genius to search Irradiator/Citadel.

6. Link the tokens for Genius, Link the two Genius for Amblowhale, Tunneler shuffle the two Genius and three Gigant to draw 2, Link Amblowhale and River Stormer for Genius.

7. NS Gearframe, search Irradiator/Citadel (whichever you didn't search with Genius the 2nd time). Pitch Citadel to summon Irradiator, tribute Dracossack to pop Gearframe. Banish the two Gearframes and the Box to SS Ruinforce (to a Genius zone) then target with Irradiator and tag with Citadel (to a non-Genius zone) to trigger Ruinforce and summon back the two Gearframe to Genius' zones, triggering Genius to search Derricrane.

8. Overlay the Gearframes for Gigant, detach to search Pegasus, Link Genius and Irradiator for Gadget, Gadget summon Pegasus, Pegasus revive Irradiator, Pegsus copy Irradiator, overlay for Dingirsu, Dingirsu attach Tunneler.

9. Tribute Gadget for River Stormer, Link River Stormer and Gigant for Knuckle, trigger Derricrane to SS itself, banish Gearframe, Gearframe, Harvester and Bike to SS Ruinforce, overlay Ruinforce and Derricrane for Dora.

End Board: Number 81: Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Super Dora (with Heavy Freight Train Derricrane attached), Double-Headed Anger Knuckle, Therion "King" Regulus, Machina Citadel, Dingirsu, the Orcust of the Evening Star (with Infinitrack Tunneler attached), Pendulum Scales (1/7), two draws, Amphibious Swarmship Amblowhale in the GY.

Overall Card Advantage: +8

I'm sure I'll be at this again soon, but for now this is the best board I could assemble with the initial concept, if not the best deck with which to do so.

Category: Tournament Meta Decks (OCG)

Tournament Meta Decks are current-level Meta Decks that are capable of going up against the best of the best. These are curated lists that cannot be uploaded by regular users.

Creator: Kenji Gonzales

Tournament: Yu-Gi-Oh! World Championship Asia Qualifier 2024 Philippines – June 1st 2024

Placement: 1st Place

Agent Control with Hyperion Tech

This deck focuses on controlling the field and disrupting your opponent's plays with a mix of "The Agent" monsters and hand traps.

Core Engine:

  • The Agent monsters: These form the backbone of the deck. "Venus" searches for other Agents, "Earth" negates monster effects, "Neptune" recovers resources, and "Protector of The Agents - Moon" (from the Extra Deck) provides protection.
  • Diviner of the Herald and Herald of Orange Light: This combo searches your deck for key cards and disrupts your opponent's plays.
  • Hand Traps: Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring, Effect Veiler, and Ghost Ogre & Snow Rabbit help shut down your opponent's most important effects.

Tech Choices:

  • Hyperion Package: "Master Hyperion" and "Majesty Hyperion" offer alternative win conditions and powerful effects, while "Starving Venom Fusion Dragon" (from the Extra Deck) can be a surprise removal option.
  • Nibiru, the Primal Being: A powerful board wipe to punish your opponent if they overextend.
  • Pot of Prosperity: Card draw to keep your hand rolling.
  • Super Polymerization: A versatile removal option for high-level monsters.
  • Solemn Judgment: Powerful negation for spells and traps.

Extra Deck:

The Extra Deck offers a toolbox of options for various situations. "Accesscode Talker" and "Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess" provide strong link summons, while "Knightmare Unicorn" and "I:P Masquerena" offer utility plays.

Overall Playstyle:

This deck aims to control the field with "The Agent" monsters and hand traps, then win through chip damage or OTKs with "Hyperion" monsters or Link Summons. It utilizes a variety of tech cards to adapt to different strategies.

deck_excerpt: Is Kash really still viable for Masterduel ladder despite all the banlist hits it has received? YES IT IS!
deck_description:
Kashtira is a solid anti-meta strategy to counter all the graveyard dependent strategies running around this tier 1 "fire format."

Kashtira is unbelievably powerful - but it has one main weakness... IT'S VASTLY INCONSISTENT! On top of that, Fenrir has finally been limited to 1 and Unicorn is now semi-limited at 2!

This weakness is fixed with Small World, which serves as 3 extra cards of every single card in your Kashtira deck! Missing a starter? Need a boardbreaker going second? Require a handtrap to to strengthen your gamestate? Search for it with Small World!

Reveal Droll -> Gadarla -> Kashtira Unicorn

Reveal Ash Blossom -> Droll -> Kashtira Unicorn

Reveal Lava Golem -> Gadarla -> Kashtira Unicorn

Reveal Maxx "C" -> Kashtira Fenrir -> Planet Pathfinder

Category: Tournament Meta Decks (TCG)

Tournament Meta Decks are current-level Meta Decks that are capable of going up against the best of the best. These are curated lists that cannot be uploaded by regular users.

Creator: Alexis Stefano Fabricio Olmedo

Tournament: Argentina National Championship 2024 – June 1st 2024

Placement: Top 4

Idiots Guide to Vampires:
The way Vampires work is that you send vampire monsters to the graveyard and they activate effects to summons themselves and search other vampire cards. Vampire Ghost and Uni-Zombie are starters, with vampire ghost being the better of the two. Both those monsters and the spells; Vampire Desires, Foolish Burial, Lightning Vortex, and Twin twister send monsters to the graveyard from your hand or deck. You want to send Vampire Retainer and Vampire Familiar monster to the graveyard as they search for Vampire cards upon activating their effects in the graves to summon themselves.
Optional:
1) You can also have Vampire Ghost in the graveyard for extra normal summons(works on opponent turn since its a quick effect, you can dodge targeted negation of monsters on the field by tributing them off), you can also summon Vampire Vamp to steal the opponent's monster.
2) Vampire Grace special summons itself if from the graveyard another Vampire monster is special summoned onto your field for 2k LP.
3) Vampire Voivode, special summons itself from the graveyard if an enemy special summons from the graveyard and you have 2 monsters on the field.

Lastly, you can use Extra Deck Monsters - Vampire Sucker and Vampire Fascinator to summon monsters onto the field you can use as material for summoning the Zombie Vampire. You won't be able to attack with all you monsters if you use Shadow Vampire's effect, hence you need Vampire Domination to stop your opponent. Vampire Domination is a counter trap like Solemn Judgment with no LP cost if you want to always have on the field at the end of the turn. Vampire Awakening targets are Vampire Crimson for destruction protection, Vampire Fraulein for battle dmg protection, Vampire Familiar to for Vampire monster search, and Vampire Retainer for Vampire Spell searcher.

The Charmers are for when you summon monsters for your opponents graveyard or steal them and you want to summon something more better in their graveyard instead. Get rid of monsters like Baroness de Fleur, Snake Eyes/Promethean Princess, and the Light Charmer because Light is the 2nd most played attribute.

"In conclusion its a great going second deck as well."

Category: Tournament Meta Decks (TCG)

Tournament Meta Decks are current-level Meta Decks that are capable of going up against the best of the best. These are curated lists that cannot be uploaded by regular users.

Creator: Allessandro A.

Tournament: Switzerland National Championship 2024 – June 1st 2024

Budget Purrely, 2nd Zeus can be subbed for SP but I don't have one yet.

This isnt an exact deck profile but its a good example of one.

Hello, welcome! 

This punk deck is actually quite fun when you understand how to play it. Unlike the BASED SUSHIP v2 deck (link in the comments) I think this could actually be good and somewhat playable.This deck focuses on paying LP to activate effects to get out powerful synchros like Ukiyoe-P.U.N.K. Amazing Dragon and Psychic End Punisher whilst utilising the HORUS engine to not only synchro them off for the monsters mentioned priorly but to also control the board using their effects also you cauld overlay them for some pretty powerful rank 8 monsters.

Some ratios you MUST keep the same (ish) are:

    - 3 Noh-P.U.N.K. Ze Amin 

    - 2 Ukiyoe-P.U.N.K. Sharakusai 

    - 1 Joruri-P.U.N.K. Madame Spider 

    - 1 or 2 Gagaku-P.U.N.K. Wa Gon

    - 2 Noh-P.U.N.K. Deer Note

    - 2 Noh-P.U.N.K. Foxy Tune

    - 1 Noh-P.U.N.K. Ogre Dance  

    - 2 P.U.N.K. JAM Extreme Session 

    - 1 Joruri-P.U.N.K. Dangerous Gabu 

    - 2 Emergency Teleport 

 Extra Deck:

    - 1 or 2 Ukiyoe-P.U.N.K. Rising Carp 

    -1 or 2 Ukiyoe-P.U.N.K. Amazing Dragon 

    - 1 or 2 P.U.N.K. JAM Dragon Drive 

    - 1 Psychic End Punisher 

The P.U.N.K engine allows us to go into very powerful synchros that clear the bord (sort of) and allow us to push for game and act as the big boss monster(s) that we end on. they also have level 8s which allow us to make strong rank 8s, using the horus cards, or to synchro with the level 3s to make the synchro boss monsters.

example combos:

Emergency Teleport or Noh-P.U.N.K. Ze Amin and a couple of discards

special / normal summon Noh-P.U.N.K. Ze Amin > pay 600 lifepoints; add Noh-P.U.N.K. Foxy Tune > Noh-P.U.N.K. Foxy Tune effect sending itself and one other card; special summon Noh-P.U.N.K. Deer Note > synchro summon using Noh-P.U.N.K. Ze Amin and Noh-P.U.N.K. Deer Note to make P.U.N.K. JAM Dragon Drive > set up the chain like:

chain link 1 Noh-P.U.N.K. Deer Note 

chain link 2 P.U.N.K. JAM Dragon Drive 

chain link 3 Noh-P.U.N.K. Ze Amin (for chain blocking:) )

                                                                                            RESOLVE

Noh-P.U.N.K. Ze Amin add 600 ATK to P.U.N.K. JAM Dragon Drive > P.U.N.K. JAM Dragon Drive pay 600 lifepoints; add a level 3 psychic tuner (like Ukiyoe-P.U.N.K. Sharakusai or Noh-P.U.N.K. Ze Amin for follow-up, or Ghost Ogre & Snow Rabbit ) > Noh-P.U.N.K. Deer Note summon back the Noh-P.U.N.K. Ze Amin > synchro the Noh-P.U.N.K. Ze Amin and the P.U.N.K. JAM Dragon Drive to make a level 11 synchro monster, for example Ukiyoe-P.U.N.K. Amazing Dragon to pop upto 3 cards you opponent controls.

 

Emergency Teleport or Ukiyoe-P.U.N.K. Sharakusai  + any other P.U.N.K monster

special / normal summon Ukiyoe-P.U.N.K. Sharakusai > pay 600 lifepoints; fusion summon Ukiyoe-P.U.N.K. Rising Carp using Ukiyoe-P.U.N.K. Sharakusai and the other P.U.N.K monster > Ukiyoe-P.U.N.K. Rising Carp tribute itself to summon out 2 P.U.N.K monsters Noh-P.U.N.K. Ze Amin and Gagaku-P.U.N.K. Wa Gon > Gagaku-P.U.N.K. Wa Gon pay 600; add a copy of P.U.N.K. JAM Extreme Session  > activate P.U.N.K. JAM Extreme Session > Noh-P.U.N.K. Ze Amin pay 600 lifepoints; add Noh-P.U.N.K. Foxy Tune > field spell trigger; draw a card ... continue the previous combo untill you get to the level 11 but now you have an extra level 3 tuner on field.

Alternatively, you can rewind back to the two level 3s on field and:

overlay Noh-P.U.N.K. Ze Amin and Gagaku-P.U.N.K. Wa Gon for a Ghostrick Alucard > stack ontop an Ghostrick Angel of Mischief > Ghostrick Angel of Mischief detatch a card; add Ghostrick Shot > Ghostrick Shot special summon back the Ghostrick Alucard > stack ontop an Ghostrick Angel of Mischief > overlay both Ghostrick Angel of Mischiefs for a Number F0: Utopic Future (> you can go battle phase to steal a monster) > stack ontop of that a Number F0: Utopic Draco Future > attack with that for 3000 damage > stack ontop of that a Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder.

A 4 material zeus; thats 2 board wipes!! 

 

For the HORUS engine i play:

    - 3 Imsety, Glory of Horus 

    - 2 Hapi, Guidance of Horus 

    - 2 Qebehsenuef, Protection of Horus 

    - 2 Duamutef, Blessing of Horus 

    - 2 or 3 King's Sarcophagus 

    + a bunch of rank 8s

I'ts a small-ish engine but its very powerful, it controls the board and works wonders in extending our P.U.N.K plays. It mainly provides non-targeting removal (not destruction as to not trigger the all mighty fire king deck) wich is allways loved, and some beautiful banishment suffleing allowing recursion for our P.U.N.K monsters banished to activate our field spell.

A very basic Imsety, Glory of Horus combo:

Imsety, Glory of Horus and a couple discards

Imsety, Glory of Horus discard itself and another card; add King's Sarcophagus > activate King's Sarcophagus > King's Sarcophagus effect on field discarding a card; send a 'horus" monster to the grave > special summon out Imsety, Glory of Horus and the other sent horus card (> overlay for a rank 8) 

Horus basically does a few things:

  -Imsety, Glory of Horus searches for King's Sarcophagus and, non-targeting, removes a card from field.

      This allows us to deal with fire kings' destruction effects and any cards we don't like on the field.

  -Hapi, Guidance of Horus shuffles or adds two cards in either (i think either) banishment or GY and shuffles

      If it's either players banishment or GY we can deal with pesky GY effects and FLOOWANDEREEZE YEEEEEEEEES or any banishment problems,        however if it's only ours then we still have good card recycling so both are great.

  -Qebehsenuef, Protection of Horus  prevents attacks on "horus" cards this turn.

      If this works how I think it works It's going to be great against the threat of tenpai dragon after Imsety, Glory of Horus combo pass with itself and           Qebehsenuef, Protection of Horus. 

 

Small World:

 This deck does have some room for handtraps and board breakers but for consistentcy I believe that Small World is the best card.Yes you do have P.U.N.K. JAM Dragon Drive to search an impactfull Ghost Ogre & Snow Rabbit but why not save that and use a small world instead?

The engine is built like so:

> 2 Nibiru, the Primal Being 

> 2 Ghost Ogre & Snow Rabbit 

> 2 Gadarla, the Mystery Dust Kaiju 

> 1 Nemeses Corridor 

+all the horus and P.U.N.K cards

Extra Deck:

These are just good cards and suggestions for different builds of the deck, my reason? I dont like people playing the exact deck from eachother l and in my opinion I think yu-gi-oh is better with slight variations in decks and deck sizes.

 >FUSION CARDS

   > 2 Ukiyoe-P.U.N.K. Rising Carp 

   You can play up to 2 copies of Ukiyoe-P.U.N.K. Rising Carp, I like the ratio like this because you only realy need two for combos and if you run out           Hapi, Guidance of Horus can always re-shuffle into the extra deck  

   I play Thunder Dragon Colossus because it's Thunder Dragon Colossus it's a walking floodgate any deck that dosn't play this when it can is really         missing out.

 >XYZ CARDS

  ghostrick cards:

  > 2 Ghostrick Angel of Mischief 

  > 1 Ghostrick Alucard 

  > 1 Ghostrick Shot(spell card)

  > 1 Number F0: Utopic Future

  > 1 Number F0: Utopic Draco Future

 You realy play this for the massive Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder

 rank 8s:

 The only mentionable ones i found are;

 - The Zombie Vampire 

- Number 38: Hope Harbinger Dragon Titanic Galaxy 

- Dingirsu, the Orcust of the Evening Star 

- Number 23: Lancelot, Dark Knight of the Underworld 

I can't really find a reason for playing any others but feel free to shift stuff around and find what works for you.

- Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder 

Because Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder is too good, we need to play it.

Thats mainly evrything you need to know about this deck REMEMER this isn't the best list ever so please feel free to tweak and change some aspects about the deck because yu-gi-oh isn't fun when it's the same deck evrywhere, have fun, enjoy and goodbye!

deck_name: Skull Servants of the Forbidden One
deck_excerpt: Exodia + Skull Servants + Fitting Room + Chaos

deck_description:
Contrary to the most obvious conclusion one might make at first glance, this is not actually a blind second deck. While this list absolutely has the gas and board presence necessary to confidently go second, you still prefer to go first and set up a strong board with extremely competent follow-up.

 

This deck plays in an extremely unique fashion unlike any other deck in the game, setting itself apart even from other Vaylantz lists. That being said, I've had by far the most success with Vaylantz on online ladders using these cards, and significantly more so than the old “Baronne-Avra pass” gameplan.

 

When building a board, your goals are clear: 


1. Set up GrandSolfachord Coolia with Dreamia in the scale.

2. Summon I:P Masquerena.

3. Summon Arktos.

4. Resolve Engage as many times as possible.

 

Successfully achieving these goals consistently will take practice and discipline with the Vaylantz cards. Lucky for you, I have a few tips to get you started:

 

1. If this is your first time playing Vaylantz: Don't play this deck. Find an easier list, I’ve posted plenty on this site. My recommendation is to start with Pachy or Invoked.

 

2. Once you have set up Coolia, I:P, and Arktos, you have two I:P targets: Apollousa using all four bodies (including Dreamia post-Omni), and S:P Little Knight. (If you side in Underworld Goddess for a specific matchup, this is also an option.) Most of the time, you will make Apollousa using all of your bodies in order to make your Striker Spells live. It's incredible how much stronger she is when backed up by a Widow Anchor or two (especially to steal), because suddenly a large monster or Ty-Phon doesn't necessarily immediately check your remaining board.

 

3. Beyond the Pendulum is not a once-per-turn. If it gets hand trapped, you can go for a second one, and you can even burn through a second or third one (depending on how the game is going) in a single turn to get a follow-up Shinonome after you have finished using all of your monster and scale effects. Doing so preserves Exceed the Pendulum,  making Accesscode lines smoother.

 

4. The primary times you will be able to use your Striker cards are at the start of your turn, and immediately before your Pendulum Summon. If you have two spells in the graveyard and just need a third one before drawing with Engage or stealing with Widow Anchor, wait until you've used Shinonome and therefore either Solo Activation or Wars and have linked them off for Beyond the Pendulum. If you have an extra body on board (i.e. Nazuki) after using Hornet Drones and Kagari, don't be afraid to make a second Beyond without effect so that you can resolve Engage.

 

5. Think about hands that include Droplet carefully. Going first, take care to use it for outing your own Field Spell while developing the board on the opponent’s turn, and going second look for combos with your various normal and Quick-Play Spell cards. Also, remember that Exceed the Pendulum can revive Pendulum Monsters from the Graveyard, so pitching a name for Droplet (or Knightmare Phoenix)  doesn't necessarily mean that you won't have it for the rest of the turn.

 

And with that, I refer any further questions to either the gameplay video included or to the Vaylantz Discord, a link to which is included in the full-length Vaylantz guide posted in the comment section of this deck. Feel free to @ me (Tsubatt) with any questions there, and I’ll do my best to answer!

deck_excerpt: Get and protect Fossil Dyna using the Vaylantz and Melodious engines!
deck_description: Link to the Full Vaylantz Guide included in the comment section.

A video guide is coming as soon as the written guide has been adequately updated.

 

A link to the written guide, of which an excerpt from is included here, can be found in the comments.

 

"I personally believe that the Fossil Dyna floodgate build is a great pair of training wheels for those attempting to learn the deck. It gives you a clear win condition and combo line: Summon Granite, add Pachy, normal and protect Pachy. This familiarity and linearity allows newer players to focus on developing an intuitive understanding of the archetype.

Regrettably, the simplifiers that make this build good for beginners is also what makes it suffer the most from hand traps. Avramax + Pachy is actually one of the deceivingly strongest boards this deck can produce when left uninterrupted, but also leaves you dead in the water to a myriad of interruptions and board breakers. 

This is why I believe that Fossil Dyna should eventually be abandoned once a player has a rudimentary understanding of the axis on which this Vaylantz operates. The weaknesses of the Granite combo turn from a crutch into a shackle that inhibits player growth, both within the archetype and in general."

A link to the written guide can be found in the comments.

The Vaylantz cards in this deck primarily serve as a crutch to get the a Tearlaments engine running, but offer genuine benenfits such as access to a Pendulum Summon and Beyond the Pendulum's Self-Destruction effect that assauge Tear's currently brickiness.

Shinonome can get you all the way to an established Tearlaments board using Muddy Mudragon and Beatrice in tandem with Exceed the Pendulum's effect to revive a Pendulum from the Graveyard. With a batshit insane pilot, this deck genuinely has teeth and can duke it out with the Tier 2 and Tier 1 threats.
A link to the written guide can be found in the comments.

17 "And David lamented with this lamentation over Saul and over Jonathan his son:

18 (Also he bade them teach the children of Judah the use of the bow: behold, it is written in the book of Jasher.)

19 The beauty of Israel is slain upon thy high places: how are the mighty fallen!

20 Tell it not in Gath, publish it not in the streets of Askelon; lest the daughters of the Philistines rejoice, lest the daughters of the uncircumcised triumph.

21 Ye mountains of Gilboa, let there be no dew, neither let there be rain, upon you, nor fields of offerings: for there the shield of the mighty is vilely cast away, the shield of Saul, as though he had not been anointed with oil.

22 From the blood of the slain, from the fat of the mighty, the bow of Jonathan turned not back, and the sword of Saul returned not empty.

23 Saul and Jonathan were lovely and pleasant in their lives, and in their death they were not divided: they were swifter than eagles, they were stronger than lions.

24 Ye daughters of Israel, weep over Saul, who clothed you in scarlet, with other delights, who put on ornaments of gold upon your apparel.

25 How are the mighty fallen in the midst of the battle! O Jonathan, thou wast slain in thine high places.

26 I am distressed for thee, my brother Jonathan: very pleasant hast thou been unto me: thy love to me was wonderful, passing the love of women.

27 How are the mighty fallen, and the weapons of war perished!" - 2 Samuel 1:17-27

The whole purpose of the deck was to rely on the true nature of the game and for the monsters to have faith in what God has given to them. Not relying on justifying satan's judgements. Boarbow has the Bow of Judah and everyone is believing in its' importance by trusting in what God has given.

YuGiOh "Rules":

1. PRAY before you play

2. Always represent your beliefs

3. Let others represent what they believe

- Yu-Gi-Oh is supposed to be about people believing in life by believing in what God has given them and living by that in order to not be involved with satan. Satan wants to steal this since it's jealous and prayer tortures it.

- Pendulum summoning is when multiple people get ready to share what they believe by trusting in the identities God gave them but two individuals trust in the God given identities of the summoned individuals.

- Xyz summoning is when someone gets ready to share their beliefs but 2+ individuals trust in the summoned person's God given direction.

- Synchro summoning is when someone gets ready to share their beliefs but 2+ individuals trust in the summoned person's God given identity.

- Fusion summoning is when someone gets ready to share their beliefs but multiple people trust in what God has given to the individual.

- Ritual summoning is when a person or people trust God's hand in the event that made the identity of the ritual monster and caused it to share its' new beliefs.

- Link summoning is when someone gets ready to share their beliefs but 2+ people trust in the summoned individual's ability to share what God has given them with others.

- Nekroz are about believing in what God is planning (faith) and sharing that with others.

deck_excerpt: MASTER DUEL, META DECK, TRAPTRIX, TRAMP, ANTIMETA, HORUS
deck_description: Traptrix siempre un deck confiable y con el que la mayoria se rinde si nos toca ir primero. En esta ocasion les traigo la version del deck que se basa en poder invocar a Baronne de Fleur que haca aun mas opresivo el deck con su omninegación.

This is a deck that I heavily use to ladder on Master Duel. Of course there are some noteable differences from its MD counterpart, however this is its' TCG adaptation and works just as well. The only thing that mainly hurts this version is not having 2 Called By The Graves as being able to punish handtraps is vital in allowing this deck to work (and although you can still do this, it requires having a Nouvelles monster on the field by using the counter trap card, but that doesn't always help if you have to rebuild your board). I've thoroughly tested this deck and 9/10 times, it doesn't brick (make sure to thoroughly shuffle).

Some key notes with this deck and some key cards are as follows:
- Final Attack Order. Why?
Final Attack Order is a necessary card in certain situations, but not every duel. A main thing that hurts this deck if you're not able to either Synchro or Link summon (or you have these cards in your graveyard and you haven't recycled them back in your deck), and trying to win when your opponent keeps placing cards in face-up defense position is a situation you can't keep summoning Confiras (level 2 Ritual Nouvelles Monster) using your Meat Recipe spell card, so pulling this trap card is necessary... but only if you notice your opponent keeps doing defense shenanigans.

If anyone has any questions about how any cards interact or work in the context of this deck, please be sure to let me know! ^^

deck_description:
After years and years (it's been a few months) of trying to find a home for Gameciel to wreak havoc with its non-once per turn omni-negate, it only makes sense for that home to be Dinosaurs, thanks to Kaitoptera and Horned Saurus!

Slightly tweaking Dino combos can allow you to activate Kyoutou Waterfront from the Deck and go into Saryuja Skull Dread to special summon Gameciel with max Kaiju counters and then some, like a 3 charge Apollousa and Evolzar Lars, the other omni-negate the deck has access to. Is it the optimal way to play Dinos? Probably not. It's main weaknesses lie in getting shut down by too many negates/hand traps, potentially bricking, and every combo players bane, Nibiru. However, this version of the deck feels like it'll be an interesting way to play the deck.

deck_description:
Guru Control has been tried and proven, however, it seems to have fallen from grace, and the only way people are running the deck is through the use of Red-Eyes Fusion.

The deck already bricks, and the access to Red-Eyes Fusion does not exist in Master Duel, therefore, how do we make Guru Control meta? We focus on control through floodgates, resilience through Evenly Matched, and defense through a spicy tech, Witch's Strike; we target generic negates!

Enjoy! Watch the gameplay, and feel free to subscribe! <3

deck_excerpt: So this is the circus... GAH!

deck_description: This is my superheavy samurais I have been tweaking for a while now. Main goals are to bait out opponent stoppers by utilizing all the different searcing methods available that work together, get out a crimson dragon, then a superheavy brave Masurawo to go into either cosmic blazar or hot red tyrant, and then usually making the other on the next turn if it goes that far. Gear gigant X is a good emergency searcher that gets Waukaushi, the true gas of the deck, and can become Zeus if needed. This deck is very weak to Nibiru and Droll which Therion Regulus is good at stopping, however the only way to search Regulus is with the XYZ Gigantic Champion which still leaves you open to Droll, but this deck has enough gas that with enough forethought you can play around many hand traps, including dimension shifters. I'm still tweaking this deck every day and experimented with Magical Hound as a side card and it could be a good option as well. Breakthrough skill is a sneaky trap that banishes itself as cost so as long as your opponent has a target you can remove it from the graveyard and I feel no one see's this coming at all. Hopefully you can make your opponents feel the weight of this SuperHeavy Deck!

pure purrely deck. in a nutshell:
-get my friend purrely + a cat -> xyz with any memory on hand (sleepy if no idea what to go) 

-get big black cat (through trap if not on own turn) 

-cringe while returning and handtrapping all of opponents cards

-then proceed to otk with happy or get zeus and repeat

This deck focuses on a control grind game with the main deck Fire King monsters, so it's okay to be greedy with Pot of Extravagance! Hopefully Fire King Consort Ulkanix gets cheap TCG prints.

Tech Cards

Book of Moon and Forbidden Chalice are budget alternatives to hand traps that work well when going first or second. Dinowrestler Pankratops is a great board breaker whose effect can destroy a monster or backrow. Use Fire King Avatar Rangbali's effect or Solemn Judgment to beat Evenly Matched. Send Volcanic Scattershot to the graveyard with Fire King Avatar Kirin's effect to win in time.

deck_excerpt: 1 card = Full Board + Follow-Up + Quick Effect Field Wipe! THE NEXT BEST FIRE DECK!
deck_description:
With the new support cards from the Masterduel Selection pack "Revived Legion," Salamangreat now has more consistency and power than ever before! Most notably, they have access to a quick effect one-sided field wipe of all your opponent's cards during their turn due to the "Code of Soul" enabling Pyro Phoenix's full effects! Salmangreat Weasel being a tuner allows the synchro summon of Fire Fist Horse Prince, allowing the deck to search Ash Blossom! Being able to make full use of the fire support released lately, especially Promethean Princess - in turn creating bigger and powerful boards! Featuring many 1-2 card combos and so many extenders typical of a cyberse link spam deck, Salamangreat is certainly one of the great fire powerhouses of the format! 
 
Salamangreat has certainly evolved past it's identity as a mid-range control deck centering in their archetypal trap cards Roar and Rage. Now, the intensity of the cyberse flames are on your side as 1 card combos enable a Pyro Phoenix to incinerate all of your opponent's cards! 
 
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 
ARCHETYPES AND DECKBUILDING 
 
SALAMANGREAT cards form the core of this deck, comprising of 20 cards. The three-ofs in this deck, Circle of Fire, Gazelle and Salamangreat of Fire are at 3 because they are either 1 card starters or really powerful extenders. The one-ofs in this deck generally are searched as part of the main combo, such as Weasel. Other one-ofs are also extenders and have great utility like Jack Jaguar and Foxy. 1 each of the powerful Salamangreat traps are included since they are also highly searchable, either by Gazelle or Raging Phoenix. 
 
The rest of the deck are composed of STAPLES. The usual compulsory "Maxx C" package is used to enable this deck to compete in Masterduel ladder. 11 handtraps are included simultaneously to interrupt your opponent and as Crossout targets. 2 Cynet Mining are included since it essentially functions as additional copies of Salamangreat of Fire. 
 
COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN 
 
The GAMEPLAN with Salamangreat doesn't merely revolve around setting up their traps + Accesscode OTK on turn 3 anymore - it has evolved into a more fire-based beatstick card advantage style, similar to Snake-Eyes except this time with Cyberse cards! 
 
Here is the most common and powerful Salamangreat combo has due to the new support cards: 
 
Salmangreat of Fire = Pyro Phoenix (quick effect fieldwipe due to Code of Soul) + Promethean Princess (destroy special summoned monster, resources) + EMP Meowmine (return 1 card opponent controls to hand) + Draw 1 (Salamangreat Meer) + x2 Raging Phoenix in GY (Gigantic beatsticks for follow-up OTK)
 
  1. Normal summon Salamangreat of Fire. Search Gazelle from deck (If you already have Gazelle search for your Salamangreat extender of choice).
  2. Link summon Balelynx using Salamangreat of Fire. CL1 Balelynx searches Sanctuary, CL2 Gazelle summons from hand. 
  3. Gazelle activates it's effect on summon to send Spinny from deck to GY. (If you already have Spinny in hand or GY send Jack Jaguar instead since it's a good extender). 
  4. XYZ summon Miragestallio using Gazelle + Spinny. 
  5. Activate Miragestallio's effect to summon Weasel from deck. 
  6. Link Summon Promethean Princess using Miragestallio + Baleynx + Weasel. 
  7. Activate Promethean Princess' effect to summon from GY any fire monster. 
  8. Link summon Raging Phoenix using Promethean Princess + fire monster. 
  9. Activate Salamangreat Sanctuary.
  10. Link summon Raging Phoenix with Raging Phoenix using the effect of Sanctuary. 
  11. Raging Phoenix searches from deck Will of the Salamangreat with it's "reincarnation summon" effect. 
  12. Activate Will of the Salamangreat's effect to summon from GY Salamangreat of Fire, Gazelle, Spinny and Weasel by targeting Raging Phoenix. 
  13. Synchro summon Fire Fist Horse Prince using Weasel + Code of Soul. 
  14. Horse Prince summons from deck Code of Soul. (If you already have Code of Soul, summon from deck Ash Blossom instead. Later on, it can be added from GY to hand).
  15. Link summon Sunlight Wolf using Horse Prince + Spinny to the link zone directly underneath Raging Phoenix.
  16. Activate Weasel's trigger effect in the GY to summon a Salamangreat monster to your opponent's side of the field then draw 1 card. 
  17. Activate Promethean Princess' effect in GY to summon itself, destroying Gazelle on your side of the field and the Salamangreat monster on your side of the field.
  18. Activate Raging Phoenix's effect in the GY to summon itself. 
  19. Link summon Spright Sprind using Salamangreat of Fire + the Raging Phoenix in the Extra Monster Zone. Sprind sends to GY EMP: Meowmine. 
  20. Link summon Pyro Pheonix in the Extra Monster Zone above Sunlight Wolf using Promethean Princess + Raging Phoenix. 
  21. Activate Sunlight Wolf's effect to recover a fire monster from your GY. (Ideally you get either Salamangreat of Fire or Ash Blossom from GY). 
  22. Set any cards like Salamangreat Roar, Imperm, Called By, etc. 
  23. During your opponent's turn, you can activate Code of Soul's effect in the GY to quick link using Pyro Phoenix to link summon another Pyro Phoenix for a full field wipe on your opponent's field. Also, when your opponent special summons a monster, you can use Promethean Princess to destroy a monster on your opponent's side of the field and your Spright Sprind. This will also trigger EMP Meowmine in the GY to return your opponent's card on the field to their hand.  
 
From a singular Salamangreat of Fire, you get a full field wipe, several removals and a draw 1! The GY and hand are full of follow-up for next turn's OTK as well! There are 8 copies of Salamangreat of Fire in a 40 card deck, giving you ample chance to draw into the 1 card combo. This endboard set-up more or less is also available even without Salamangreat of Fire if you can make Miragestallio, since making it enables full combo. 
 
Going second, you do pretty much the same thing, but instead you attempt to simplify the gamestate with your 11 handtraps and this deck's incredible consistency and extending power. Boards are cleared with Pyro Phoenix's fieldwipe combined with the incredibly high attack of Raging Phoenix! 
 
 
GENERAL TIPS
  • If Maxx "C" resolves against you and you couldn't OTK, don't play into it by going full combo - having your opponent draw 20+ cards almost always isn't worth it. 
  • True to the other cyberse combo decks, Salamangreat has many extenders like Spinny, Meer and Will of the Salamangreat that enable them to full combo even when interrupted. Keep this in mind as you plow through your opponent's interruption and handtraps!
  • Much like the other meta fire decks in this format, Salamangreat benefits greatly from Hiita and Promethean Princess. After Promethean Princess summons from your GY a Salamangreat combo piece or 1 card starter, you can proceed to full combo! 
  •  
 
CONCLUDING REMARKS
 
Before the Selection Pack "Revived Legion" came out in Masterduel, Salamangreat seemed like a weaker version of Mathmech. The deck builds up to 1-2 backrow interruptions and removal backed by mass handtraps then OTKs turn 3 with Accesscode Talker. That seems boring and redundant when comparing Salamangreat to the other powerhouse Cyberse decks given the superior power and consistency of Mathmech and @Ignister. However, now the strategy has a unique fiery gameplan, playstyle and "flavour," with newly released cards like Raging Phoenix, Code of Soul and Weasel to blow up your opponent's entire board! 
 
With these powerups, Salamangreat has further increased in power to comfortably compete in Masterduel ladder, making it an ideal deck to reach Masters 1 with due to it's adaptability, consistency and simplicity! 
 
GLHF Duelists!

deck_excerpt: The most boring deck in Edison
deck_description:
Deck aims to be a rogue answer to a "solved" format. The basic idea is to deffend your life points by locking your opponents hitters with Chains and Wheels, or providing fat defense with Metal Reflect Slime, keeping yourself safe as you search for Blaze Accelerator. Once the Accelerator is active, you;re ready to whipe their field, and resupply your backrow using cards like Magic Planter and Royal Firestorm Guards that also shuffles back Shells to allow you to use the Accelerator again. Aside from being the deck's main win condition, Uria can also be discarded with Accelerator to blow a card up, and can also be shuffled with the Guards. You also deploy a small burn engine in form of Solar Flare Dragon and Nightamre Wheel to peck at your opponent's LP, or use Zoma The Spirit to punish them for summoning a beefy Synchro Monster (which can sometime end the game on its own).

You rinse and repeat until your opponent burns through their resources, then finish the game in a single blow from Uria.

deck_excerpt: Fusions are pretty butt but cool asf
deck_description: Fusions are pretty butt but cool asf

Thunder Dragon Chaos Fusion

This deck combines the aggressive swarming of Thunder Dragons with the powerful fusion capabilities of the Bystial archetype and a touch of Chaos magic.

Core Engine:

  • Thunder Dragons (Thunder Dragon, Thunder Dragondark, Thunder Dragonroar, Thunder Dragonhawk, Thunder Dragonmatrix): These monsters form the backbone of the deck, swarming the field and generating resources for Link Summons and fusions.
  • Bystial Monsters (The Bystial Lubellion, Bystial Druiswurm, Bystial Magnamhut, Bystial Baldrake): These provide search, hand advantage, and powerful monster effects while fueling the graveyard for fusions.

Fusion Power:

  • Thunder Dragon Fusion and Bystial Spells: These cards allow for powerful fusions like Thunder Dragon Titan, Thunder Dragon Colossus, and The Bystial Lubellion.

Chaos Touch:

  • Black Luster Soldier - Envoy of the Beginning, The Chaos Creator, Chaos Space: These cards add a surprise factor and can be used for game-ending plays with the right setup.

Tech Choices:

  • Batteryman Solar: Provides additional searching and graveyard setup for fusions.
  • Hand Traps (Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring, Effect Veiler, Ghost Ogre & Snow Rabbit): Disrupt your opponent's plays and maintain card advantage.
  • Allure of Darkness: Thins the deck and fuels graveyard effects.
  • Called by the Grave and Solemn Judgment: Powerful staples for countering your opponent's strategies.

Extra Deck:

The Extra Deck provides a toolbox for various situations:

  • Thunder Dragon Fusions (Thunder Dragon Titan, Thunder Dragon Colossus): Powerful boss monsters for overwhelming your opponent.
  • Generic Link Monsters (Accesscode Talker, Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess, Knightmare Unicorn, Knightmare Phoenix): Offer utility and disruption against various threats.

Overall Playstyle:

This deck aims to aggressively swarm the field with Thunder Dragons, utilize Bystial effects to gain advantage, and then use powerful fusions or Chaos monsters to close out the game. The hand traps and staple cards provide disruption and ensure you can adapt to your opponent's strategy.

Weaknesses:

  • The deck can be bricky if you don't draw the right hand with monsters and searchers.
  • It's vulnerable to hand traps if you can't establish your plays quickly.

Overall, this deck is a fun and versatile option for Duelists who enjoy a mix of aggressive swarming and powerful fusion plays.
